sian tree-feller's attempt at reform has much to prove, writes Shawn Donnan. There is nothing more difficult in business than repairing a tarnished reputation. So when Asia Pulp &Paper, an Indonesian company with a long history of bulldozing its way through tropical jungle, last August signed a deal to mend its environmental ways with the World Wide Fund for Nature, it was greeted cautiously.\par \par \uc2 The deal ended years of sparring between the company and WWF over Sumatra's forests and gave APP, which in 2001 was responsible for the largest (Dollars 13.9bn) debt default in emerging markets history, six months to draft an "action plan".\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 If all went well, WWF would some day endorse the plan and everyone would emerge a winner. Paper buyers in Europe, Japan and the US would be able to sell APP paper to customers increasingly demanding environmentally friendly products. Sumatran forests that environmentalists claim are "twice as diverse as anything found in the Amazon" would be saved. And APP and Indonesia's Widjaja family, its controlling shareholders, would take a small step forwards in their corporate rehabilitation.\par \par \uc2 Now the six months are up and the real test is looming. On Wednesday in Paris APP is scheduled to meet European paper buyers and WWF representatives to brief them on its plan. And on Thursday, the day the current WWF agreement expires, APP is due to release the plan publicly.\par \par \uc2 But WWF officials are displaying a distinct grumpiness. "At this point we are not satisfied with their action plan," says Nazir Foead, the group's lead negotiator with APP.\par \par \uc2 As a result, APP may be about to lose its biggest ally in a rare experiment in bringing first-world-style \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  to a developing country. Moreover, the WWF faces what would be a severe blow to its efforts to push for constructive engagement with companies such as APP. And that could prompt green groups to return to calling for boycotts, tactics that have until now done little to halt forest destruction.\par \par \uc2 "We're very much in the hot seat on this," says one senior WWF official.\par \par \uc2 APP's plan calls for measures to ensure illegally felled wood does not make it into its pulp mills and for a total move by 2007 to using the environmentally friendly plantations that now provide about 30 per cent of its wood. APP is also pledging Dollars 7m (Pounds 3.7m) and 70,000 hectares of Sumatran forest it controls to establish a conservation area.\par \par \uc2 The company insists that it is turning over a new leaf, regardless of WWF's involvement. "We are committed to the action plan and will implement it," says Arian Ardie, APP's director of "sustainability and stakeholder engagement".\par \par \uc2 Environmentalists remain wary of what they call a possible "greenwash". They say Mr Ardie, a recent arrival at APP who drafted the action plan with the help of Ogilvy, the global public relations company, appears to be well-intentioned but unable to speak for the Widjajas on big institutional changes.\par \par \uc2 Mr Ardie denies that. "We would not have been able to make multi-million-dollar commitments without the full support of the shareholders," he says.\par \par \uc2 But WWF officials call APP's plan half-hearted. Most of the 70,000 hectares APP wants to set aside for protection is already designated as a conservation area, they say, and most is "deep swamp", too expensive for\par \par \uc2 APP to harvest. APP's pledge to turn wholly to plantations by 2007 also strikes other environmentalists as self-serving. "By 2007 there will be no (natural) forest left to pulp" within easy reach of its mills, says one close watcher of APP's operations.\par \par \uc2 WWF wants a moratorium on harvesting natural forests while social and environmental impact studies are carried out. The studies would take only a few months, they argue, and APP could use its plantations to supply mills in the meantime. Without a moratorium, APP will "give WWF no option but to alter its engagement position drastically", says Mr Foead.\par \par \uc2 APP argues that is unrealistic. "Many of the things being suggested are neither necessary nor economically responsible," says Mr Ardie.\par \par \uc2 But this time the bargaining power may lie with the WWF, thanks to its growing links with buyers in Europe and Japan and big American retailers such as Staples.\par \par \uc2 "To some extent APP don't have much choice. Unless APP can switch over and sell everything they are making to China or India, APP has to deal with these problems," says Nigel Sizer, a forest campaigner for The Nature Conservancy, a US-based charity.\par \par \uc2 Whether or not it lasts, APP's relationship with WWF could signal a new trend in the movement for \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Until now, says Daniel Litvin, author of Empires of Profit: Commerce, Conquest and Corporate Responsibility, most activist pressure on companies working in the developing world has been focused on multinationals. "This sort of example with APP is quite unusual." \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9