aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Analysts and corporate responsibility\par \par \uc2 Should City analysts pay serious attention to the social responsibility of the companies they cover?\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Yes, according to the Association of British Insurers and a group of fellow-minded fund managers who this week called on the analysts to do precisely this. "We are determined that this is taken seriously," said Peter Montagnon, the ABI's head of investment affairs.\par \par \uc2 At present brokers' analysts pay little or no overt attention to so-called "\b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 " - companies' attitudes to social, ethical and environmental issues - even though a sizeable cottage industry has grown up in certain parts of the investment industry to monitor what businesses are doing.\par \par \uc2 That suggests there is little useful investment information in the fashion for CSR. Financial markets may not be as efficient as theory suggests, but the City's collective greed and brainpower ought to be able to spot any significant source of competitive advantage.\par \par \uc2 The ABI and its allies insist that there is a link between CSR and long-term business performance and they published a report this week to back this up. But it was a bit of a damp squib, involving no original data. It merely summarised existing research, which finds no clear evidence that socially responsible investing confers any long-term advantage. It might produce higher returns and is unlikely to bring increased risk or lower returns - a proposition unlikely to get an analyst's pulse racing.\par \par \uc2 However, the whole subject is bedevilled with the problem of defining CSR. The ABI, sensibly, does not see itself as on an ethical crusade, or setting particular standards. It simply argues that companies need to be aware of, and manage, the risks they face from social and \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  issues, and it wants them to spell out in their annual reports whether they are on top of the subject.\par \par \uc2 This is common sense. Society is casting an increasingly critical gaze over business standards of behaviour and no well-managed company will ignore this. Defined as narrowly as this, CSR is simply part of a spectrum of risk management issues that any good, forward thinking board should be watching very closely. And logic suggests there ought to be a connection between good management and good long term performance.\par \par \uc2 But that does not mean CSR can necessarily be isolated as a significant contributor to performance. It may simply be a sign of overall good management, rather than a factor in its own right. There are many other risks - economic, regulatory, strategic - that will carry far more weight in determining performance.\par \par \uc2 So analysts may already be implicitly incorporating a quite sufficient element of CSR in their investment recommendations, since these are based not merely on financial numbers but also on an estimate of management's overall strengths and weaknesses.\par \par \uc2 A final puzzle: if fund managers really do believe they can gain an investment edge by investing in companies with good CSR, how can they possibly want brokers' analysts to focus on this area? For if the analysts did, the fund managers' advantage would be arbitraged away as others spotted the same opportunities.\par \par \uc2 Put this to the activist fund managers and they mutter about just wanting "general" information from the analysts, which they can investigate further. So, got that analysts? You must take the issue seriously; but not too seriously. It may not be worth the effort.\par \par \uc2 Bubble trouble\par \par \uc2 On the surface, all still seems well in the housing market. This week the housebuilders' results season got under way with impressive figures from George Wimpey. Over among the mortgage lenders, HBOS reported a 29 per cent jump in profits. James Crosby, the chief executive, who has been right about the housing market boom so far, predicted it would continue to be underpinned by low interest rates, a good employment market and a shortage of stock.\par \par \uc2 However, even HBOS is tightening its lending criteria and the latest statistics provide fresh signs of bubble trouble. Price inflation, runs conventional wisdom, will gradually cool over the next two years as Bank of England interest rate rises engineer a soft landing. But figures from Nationwide this week suggest prices rose at their fastest pace in almost two years this month, for an annual inflation rate of 17.1 per cent.\par \par \uc2 The higher house rises go, the harder the landing is likely to be. And with an increasing proportion of stock in the hands of speculative buy-to-let investors, and net rental yields falling, it may not take a huge rise in interest rates or unemployment to have a depressing effect. The expectation of falling prices could do so. Consumers' unwillingness to rein in debt is a huge headache for the Bank of England's monetary policy committee. It provides some vindication for Sir Andrew Large, its arch hawk, who in recent months repeatedly voted for an interest rate rise, twice as sole dissenter.\par \par \uc2 martin.dickson@ft.com \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 ccsr : \uc2 Corporate Social Responsibility | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RE\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 uk : \uc2 United Kingdom | eecz : \uc2 European Union Countries | eurz : \uc2 Europe | weurz : \uc2 Western Europe\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b PUB\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 The Financial Times Limited (AAIW/EIW)\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trga