pnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Jeffrey Hollender's business card is printed on recycled paper using soy-based inks. His toilet paper is whitened with eco-friendly hydrogen peroxide rather than chlorine bleach. His switchboard soothes callers with woodland birdsong.\par \par \uc2 But the founder and chief executive of Seventh Generation, the largest US brand of "green" household products, including tissue, soaps and cleaners, admits that the struggle to be socially responsible is unrelenting.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 His latest dilemma: should Seventh Generation continue to supply Albertsons, a supermarket group that is locked in an industrial dispute with employees in southern California?\par \par \uc2 The issue was raised by a Seventh Generation employee with moral doubts about delivering products across picket lines.\par \par \uc2 At most companies, this outbreak of social conscience would have travelled no further up the corporate hierarchy than the employee's immediate supervisor - if voiced at all. At Seventh Generation, it ended up on the boss's desk.\par \par \uc2 "I was thrilled that someone who is probably the lowest-paid person in the company felt safe enough to go to the sales manager, and that the sales manager took it seriously," says Mr Hollender.\par \par \uc2 For the record, Seventh Generation will continue to supply Albertsons. It would not be fair, says the 49-year-old entrepreneur, to change the rules halfway though the trading relationship. The company's contract with Albertsons says nothing about industrial disputes.\par \par \uc2 However, the broader issue - how Seventh Generation should respond to industrial action in its supply and demand chains - will be considered by the company's "values and operations committee" so that a policy can be put in place.\par \par \uc2 Surely this endless hand-wringing over values and ethics detracts from the serious business of commerce?\par \par \uc2 After all, while Seventh Generation is a leader in the nascent market for eco-friendly household products, it remains tiny compared with mainstream competitors such as Unilever, Procter &Gamble and Kimberly Clark.\par \par \uc2 Mr Hollender's answer is twofold. First, he points to mounting evidence that socially responsible companies outperform their less morally engaged rivals.\par \par \uc2 Witness last week's edict from the Association of British Insurers that public companies should publish assessments of any environmental risks they run. The trade association for some of the largest UK institutional investors was sending a clear message: bad behaviour is bad business.\par \par \uc2 This kind of shareholder activism, combined with the growing importance of intangible assets such as brand and reputation, is moving \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  into the mainstream.\par \par \uc2 Second, he says that dealing with this kind of dilemma is central to his role as chief executive:\par \par \uc2 "I'm not there to go out and sell. I'm not there to create the advertising. It's not my job to manage the supply chain. It is my job to manage the culture and values of the company. This is where I can make the biggest contribution."\par \par \uc2 This is less avant garde than it sounds. Many of today's more thoughtful chief executives regard their primary role as developing competences or skills within their organisations.\par \par \uc2 Usually, this means trying to create a culture that is entrepreneurial, innovative or risk-taking in the best sense. At Seventh Generation, it means fostering a culture that confronts difficult questions about ethics, the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and social responsibility.\par \par \uc2 How does he measure progress towards this goal? While sales and profits are easily measured, competences and cultures do not slot so easily into spreadsheets.\par \par \uc2 Mr Hollender concedes: "You can measure [your company's] CO emissions. You can measure how much rainforest you cut down. But how do you measure whether you have created the kind of culture where people understand the values and will ask the right questions? It is not easy."\par \par \uc2 Seventh Generation relies on a mix of employee surveys, feedback from customers and suppliers and gut instinct. In a small company, employing fewer than 100 people, Mr Hollender can remain in close touch with most aspects of the business.\par \par \uc2 With sales growing at 20-40 per cent annually, however, the Vermont-based company looks set to become more than just another well-meaning minnow. This is sure to pose new challenges.\par \par \uc2 In What Really Matters*, published last month, Mr Hollender pinpoints scale as one of the biggest issues facing environmentally minded businesses.\par \par \uc2 Countless entrepreneurs have proved that when it comes to creating a socially responsible business, small is beautiful. A principled core group of founders - think of Ben Cohen of Ben &Jerry's ice-cream or Anita Roddick of Body Shop - can maintain tight control.\par \par \uc2 But what happens when the business grows? Can big business behave well, too?\par \par \uc2 The issue is especially relevant at a time when many high-profile US companies have been sold to food giants.\par \par \uc2 Ben &Jerry's is now part of Unilever; Stonyfield Farm, a big producer of organic yoghurt, is a division of Danone, the French foods group; Nantucket Nectars, the fruit juice brand, is part of Cadbury-Schweppes.\par \par \uc2 For Seventh Generation, an acid test will come if the company grows big enough to get on the radar of Wal-Mart, the world's largest retailer.\par \par \uc2 "I'd have grave doubts about selling Seventh Generation products through Wal-Mart," says Mr Hollender. His difficulty with the discount retailer stems from the low wages paid to its mainly non-union shop workers.\par \par \uc2 "Then again," he adds, "the counter-argument is that stores like Wal-Mart are merely the conduit through which you get better products into the hands of consumers. Don't shoot the messenger." At this stage the debate is hypothetical. But for companies that are serious about \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 , there are no easy answers.\par \par \uc2 * What Really Matters by Jeffrey Hollender and Stephen Fenichell, published by Basic Books, $26 \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 i4132 : \uc2 Ice Cream/Frozen Desserts | i41 : \uc2 Food/Beverages/Tobacco | i413 : \uc2 Dairy Products | i414 : \uc2 Food Preserving/Speciality Foods | i4141 : \uc2 Frozen Food | ifood : \uc2 Food Products\cell \pard \ql