clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b SN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Financial Times (FT.Com)\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b SC\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 FTCOM\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LA\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (c) 2004 The Financial Times Limited. All rights reserved \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 When US institutional investors representing assets worth hundreds of billions of dollars met last November at the United Nations to demand that US regulators, corporate boards and Wall Street companies increase their disclosure of risks posed by climate change, it marked a step forward in raising the awareness of capital markets to global warming.\par \par \uc2 Yet, despite increasing evidence of how corporations and capital markets could be affected by such regulations, few finance or accounting professors at business schools are including climate-change related issues into their teaching.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The reasons why finance professionals need to wake up to climate change certainly seem compelling. As the aggregators of risk, insurers must bear the cost of environmental disasters and catastrophic weather incidents. Laws covering pollution, product liability and public nuisance will be powerful tools in forcing companies to improve their environmental performance.\par \par \uc2 Regulations driven by public policy will have an impact, too. Banks may suffer from bad loans to companies that have not prepared for new emissions trading schemes (ETS) which, with charges per tonne for emissions set to be introduced in Europe, Japan, Canada and some US states, could seriously reduce margins.\par \par \uc2 Plenty of business schools are incorporating sustainability issues into the MBA curriculum. However, it remains largely the preserve of management professors, who are teaching the subject as part of the more general corporate citizenship course material that includes topics relating to ethics and \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 "The reality is that financial analysts and professors of finance are not switched on to these issues," says Gavin Power, a senior adviser of the Global Compact, a United Nations' initiative that urges multinationals to support human rights, labour and environmental standards.\par \par \uc2 "Part of the reason is that they have largely heard of these issues from an ethical standpoint rather than the business case. That's key in this, because when you talk to the financial community, you must frame this in business terms as risk mitigation and risk management."\par \par \uc2 Raymond Gorman, professor of finance at Miami University of Ohio, is one of a handful of academics taking a more hard-edged look at the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Prof Gorman teaches an undergraduate course in sustainability - available as an elective for MBA students - that introduces financial instruments such as catastrophe bonds and catastrophe options as ways of sharing the risk of climate change with the capital markets. "My personal opinion is that we're ignoring a lot of environmental issues," he says. "But I don't get a lot of sense that there are many people who share my concern in the finance profession. There are in management, economics and even accounting - but less so in finance."\par \par \uc2 A few schools are attempting to tackle global warming from a financial perspective. Weatherproof Your Business, an executive programme at Pennsylvania State University's Smeal College of Business has weather experts in its faculty and focuses on managing earnings volatility by using weather derivatives and other hedging techniques.\par \par \uc2 New courses for MBA students are being pioneered. At New York's Columbia Business School, Bruce Usher, adjunct professor of finance and CEO of EcoSecurities Group, a greenhouse gas advisory company, is launching a course this autumn on finance and sustainability.\par \par \uc2 This will cover three main areas: capital markets and how their principles and mechanisms are being applied to environmental issues via regimes such as the European Union ETS; investment management (socially responsible investment, and private equity and venture capital markets); and commercial banking (micro-finance in both the US and developing countries and project finance in developing countries).\par \par \uc2 Last year's Beyond Grey Pinstripes report from the Aspen Institute and the World Resources Institute, highlighted examples of finance and accounting courses that have environmental content. Among them are Yale School of Management's Private Investment and the \b \highlight22\uc2 Environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 ; Kenan-Flagler Business School's Financial Analysis: Integrating Sustainability; and University of Vermont School of Business Administration's Accounting and the \b \highlight22\uc2 Environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 However, the report concludes that the "integration of social and environmental topics into required courses remains limited".\par \par \uc2 Those programmes that do exist often remain the initiatives of individual faculty members with a particular interest in finance and sustainability, such as professors Usher and Gorman.\par \par \uc2 Part of the difficulty schools face in presenting the risks and financial implications of climate change for business is that, since global warming is a long-term issue, little corporate experience exists that might feed into course material.\par \par \uc2 "There are virtually no cases on it," says Prof Usher. "Cases always lag because they're based on something that actually happened, and you're never going to have a case that's based on something that's going to happen in the future - so that's an issue, because global warming is in the future."\par \par \uc2 Another problem is that recruiters are not yet coming to business school campuses looking for graduates whose finance and accounting skills have an environmental bent.\par \par \uc2 Research produced by Innovest Strategic Advisors for the Carbon Disclosure Project gives some indication of the lack of awareness of the investment community and the financial sector. Despite the report's evidence that share values in emission-intensive companies failing to address global warming could fall by up to 40 per cent, at least one leading bank and one leading insurance company replied to the queries that, as financial services concerns, they would not be affected by climate change.\par \par \uc2 "Companies make statements that they take global warming seriously," says Prof Usher. "But I don't see that, from a financial analysis perspective and financial decision-making perspective, they have been affected."\par \par \uc2 This is, no doubt, because the effects of climate change itself remain an uncertain area and too far in the future. However, legislation driven by public policy - particularly regarding carbon emissions - is on the horizon.\par \par \uc2 The European Union's ETS, for example, will be introduced next year, capping emissions emitted from fossil fuel-fired energy production facilities as well as from medium to large processing plants. Such legislation has concrete, immediate and serious implications for businesses and capital markets.\par \par \uc2 Eileen Claussen, president of the Pew Center on Global Climate Change, argues that business school faculty and MBA students should be at the forefront of raising awareness of such issues. "One way to get this kind of thinking is through MBA programmes," she says.\par \par \uc2 "Because if they don't deal with it, you don't have it built in at the middle level and upward."\par \par \uc2 "MBA students are absolutely central to this," says Mr Power. "They are creating the business leaders of tomorrow - and it's absolutely crucial that MBA programmes begin to incorporate this in the teaching of finance and accounting." \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 i983 : \uc2 Educational Services | ibcs : \uc2 Business/Consumer Services | i9831 : \uc2 Business Schools\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 nedc : \uc2 Commentary/Opinion | c31 : \uc2 Marketing | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | ncat : \uc2 Content Types\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clver