d\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b PG\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 Page 10\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LA\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (c) 2004 The Financial Times Limited. All rights reserved \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 A trickle of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  surveys has turned into a flood.Alison Maitland talks to the people on the receiving end. For those seeking to hold companies to account for their behaviour, transparency has become a buzzword over the past few years. But how much transparency is enough? Have demands for ever-greater disclosure gone too far?\par \par \uc2 Take the workload created by these demands at BT, the telecommunications group. The company receives more than 200 questionnaires a year about its governance and corporate responsibility practices, says Chris Tuppen, head of sustainable development and corporate accountability. Requests for information come from big government clients, investors, academics and consultancies.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 "In 1990, there were probably about five questionnaires a year. It has grown exponentially since about 2000," he says. "Some of the questionnaires have 80 to 100 questions, often with sub-questions." One person now devotes two to three days a week responding to these questionnaires, at a direct cost to the company of Pounds 25,000 (Dollars 45,000)a year.\par \par \uc2 BT is not alone. Concern about the risks posed by poor governance, ethical lapses or environmental mismanagement have swelled requests for detailed information about whether companies are meeting acceptable standards.\par \par \uc2 "There is no question that there has been a huge increase over the last couple of years," says Al Loehnis, a director of the Investor Relations Society, a European professional body. "It genuinely has created problems at companies."\par \par \uc2 The resulting "questionnaire fatigue" afflicts investor relations officers, company secretaries and corporate responsibility managers, who face piles of paper and online forms that often cover similar ground, but each from a slightly different angle.\par \par \uc2 Bridget Walker, head of investor relations at Scottish &Newcastle, the international brewing group, says many questions are irrelevant. The concerns that S&N must address are those that can directly affect its reputation, such as responsible alcohol consumption or labour standards in its operations in emerging markets. Questions such as how much electricity it uses in each of its UK sites are a side issue. "We don't need to talk about this."\par \par \uc2 There is pressure, however, to take part in big questionnaire and ranking exercises, such as the FTSE4Good Index and the Corporate Responsibility Index run by Business in the Community, even at the risk of scoring less than brilliantly. "If we're not in it, it would look like we'd have something to hide," she says.\par \par \uc2 Some investor relations officers are particularly irked by the proliferation of ratings agencies that seek information that they then sell on to their subscribers. Real IR, a specialist magazine launched this week. quotes Andrew Griffith, head of investor relations at BSkyB, the media company, as saying: "You can't quibble with the reputable organisations. The problem is this deluge of self-appointed groups who expect you to devote significant resources to lengthy questionnaires that often appear to have been written up at home on somebody's word processor."\par \par \uc2 The quality of questionnaires varies greatly. Mr Tuppen at BT is a strong advocate of transparency and accepts that it is critical for the business to respond thoroughly to questions from customers, investors and researchers who compile respected rankings such as the FTSE4Good and Dow Jones Sustainability Indices. What annoys him are demands for information that is already available on the BT website, and questionnaires that ask the company to evaluate its own performance. He has even been asked to fill in a questionnaire on "questionnaire fatigue".\par \par \uc2 "The other frustrating thing is where you're given a series of boxes to tick and they don't match the way that you manage things in the business. Sometimes these are online questionnaires and you can't go to the next question until you've ticked the box. You're forced into answering a question when it may not be the right answer."\par \par \uc2 Some argue that this form of scrutiny, however burdensome, has to be a good thing given the gravity of recent corporate malfeasance.\par \par \uc2 Governance Metrics International is a US-based ratings agency launched in 2000 that draws up profiles of 2,100 companies worldwide from publicly available data. Its research covers nearly 500 indicators of performance. It sends these detailed profiles to each company for review and comment before distributing the ratings to its institutional investor subscribers.\par \par \uc2 "I sympathise with company officers who have to deal with a growing number of CSR and corporate governance surveys or data reviews like ours," says Howard Sherman, chief operating officer. "But there's a bigger picture. In today's market \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , consistent and high quality disclosure is key if companies want to be valued properly."\par \par \uc2 Others are doubtful that surveys are the most effective way of improving governance. Alastair Ross Goobey, chairman of the International Corporate Governance Network and former head of Hermes, the activist fund manager, says scrutiny is proper and useful, but not in the form of endless repetitive questionnaires.\par \par \uc2 "It's an absolute nightmare," he says. "Company secretaries get driven mad by the number of them. A lot of what's going on is pretty wasteful." Questionnaires tend to be blunt instruments, he says. "There's probably too much concentration on filling in questionnaires and not enough on analysing where the real risks lie. Anything which helps to stem the tide of individual questionnaires would probably be a good idea."\par \par \uc2 Help may be at hand in forthcoming draft regulations from the British government, which are expected to require companies to state what social, environmental and ethical risks they face in an "operating and financial review" in their annual report.\par \par \uc2 The London Stock Exchange has also been talking to companies and institutional investors about creating a more efficient reporting channel that could reduce the questionnaire burden. Fund managers themselves are making joint, rather than individual, requests to companies for information on certain high-profile issues such as the Carbon Disclosure Project on greenhouse gas emissions and the Pharma Project on access to drugs in developing countries.\par \par \uc2 Some ratings agencies are trying to address survey fatigue by gathering data from public sources and approaching companies only for follow-up information.\par \par \uc2 A new report into the quality of socially responsible investment research points to three organisations that are best addressing the problem of survey fatigue: Innovest and the Investor Responsibility Research Center in the US, and SAM Research in Switzerland, which compiles data for the Dow Jones Sustainability indices. Seb Beloe, co-author of the report, Values for Money, and director of research and advocacy at SustainAbility, a consultancy, says companies can also help themselves. "They should be more strategic about who they respond to and the ways in which they do that," he says. "Very few have thought about how their investor relations department can work with their CSR department to ensure they're communicating effectively."\par \par \uc2 Some companies are already being selective. The number taking part in the Business in the Community (BITC) rankings rose this year, but two of those ranked last year were absent. Reuters, the information group, pulled out on the grounds that the ranking methodology did not take enough account of the extent of its corporate responsibility work or of issues specific to media. Shell said it responded to a large number of surveys and wanted to see how the BITC system developed before deciding whether to commit resources to it again.\par \par \uc2 Businesses should only respond to questionnaires or rankings if doing so benefits them, says Peter Knight, director of Context, a sustainable development consultancy. Other inquiries should be referred to their websites - assuming the information is there.\par \par \uc2 If the questions are unfair or immaterial to their business performance, they should simply decline to answer them, he advises. "It's a bit like insurance salesmen. You don't have to talk to them".\par \par \uc2 HOW NEW TECHNOLOGY COULD HELP LIFT THE BURDEN OF SURVEY FATIGUE\par \par \uc2 Technology could eventually take the hard work out of corporate transparency. An emerging electronic reporting format known as XBRL, or Extensible Business Reporting Language, could allow investors, regulators and researchers to glean the social, environmental and governance information they need about companies almost instantly from the internet. XBRL uses a system of tags that identify individual bits of data in documents, enabling analysts and other users to assemble and compare the precise information they want rapidly and automatically.\par \par \uc2 Modelled on identification systems used to trace goods through the supply chain, it works across different software applications. Instead of trawling manually through documents on websites, researchers would be able to use their Microsoft Excel spreadsheets to search for and extract all the information they want from across the web in a matter of seconds, says Mike Willis, founding chairman of XBRL International, a consortium of accounting firms, companies and stock exchanges. So far only a few companies, including Microsoft and Wacoal, a Japanese women's wear business, are using it either internally to assemble data or to submit financial reports to the regulatory authorities. A number of regulators including the UK's Financial Services Authority have announced projects to use XBRL, says Mr Willis, a partner at PwC. But he says companies could also use XBRL to collect the data they need to produce social and environmental reports and respond to questionnaires.\par \par \uc2 He is working on a pilot with American Refining Group, a small US oil refiner, which is backed by the Caux Round Table, an international business ethics network. To become a reporting standard, large numbers of companies clearly need to adopt it. "What's required is transparency and agreement on definitions, such as what does 'employee' mean," says Mr Willis. "The software will be there by the end of the year but the definition is up to the CSR community." It will take time, but he believes it could be working in two to four years. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.xbrl.org"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 www.xbrl.org}}}\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 ccsr : \uc2 Corporate Social Responsibility | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | nanl : \uc2 Analysis | ncat : \uc2 Content Types\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trq