aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The Range Rover bumped across acres of former farmland that aggregates extraction had made as rugged and barren as the surface of the moon. The site manager - imagine Giant Haystacks in a hard hat and high-visibility waistcoat - drove me impassively to the centre of his devastated domain. No rabbit hopped. No songbird twittered. My guide pointed to a plywood structure atop a pole. "That," he said, his voice trembling with pride, "is the Owl Nesting Box."\par \par \uc2 It did not contain any owls. That site visit has come to symbolise for me the \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  movement. Here, gestures as empty as the nesting box are commonplace.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The bandwagon is bowling along at a cracking pace. A cottage industry of specialist consultancies is bombarding companies with questionnaires probing their CSR policies. About four-fifths of FTSE 100 companies now disclose social, environmental and ethical risks in their annual reports, as the Association of British Insurers requires. All quoted businesses would have to follow suit under laws planned by the government. Useless to ask the Lord, as Saint Augustine did, to be made virtuous "but not yet!"\par \par \uc2 The trend for wearing your virtuous intentions as a merit badge is disturbing because it betrays nervousness within business about public hostility to money-making. The main social responsibility of a company is to create wealth and distribute it through dividends, interest and employment. But this message is low in the mix in the burgeoning subculture of CSR, if present at all.\par \par \uc2 Will Hutton, director of the Work Foundation, says the CSR movement owes its existence to a shift in public attitudes away from the individualism of the 1980s and 1990s. Caring, sharing values are hip again, as illustrated by growth in the voluntary sector, a jump in applications for teacher training and the buzz surrounding social enterprise. Unabashed capitalism has been pushed on to the back foot by scandals such as that of Enron. "People simply do not trust the private sector to act in the public good," says Jane Hunt, a Lancaster University academic expert in nuclear waste issues.\par \par \uc2 Even a curmudgeon like me believes companies should treat their employees well and avoid damaging the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the communities where they operate. It will generally make them more profitable. But businesses should resist the insidious assumption implicit in bumf produced by the CSR movement that there is a package of actions that can make a company ethically irreproachable.\par \par \uc2 Ethics are too subjective for this. For example, making bombs that kill children is very wrong - unless, apparently, the children are in Baghdad, when the deaths, according to the government, are merely "regrettable". Employing children to stitch footballs is also wrong. But is it still wrong if they would starve without the work? You tell me.\par \par \uc2 It is the job of governments to divine the public consensus on moral issues and reflect it in laws that business should obey. The profit motive is too great a distraction for companies to portray themselves convincingly as squeaky-clean policemen of prevailing ethical standards.\par \par \uc2 BT, for instance, recently published an "independent" report on its website that largely endorsed its actions in moving some call-centre work to India at a cost of 2,000 UK jobs. The report, produced by the consultancy SustainAbility for a GBP40,000 fee, praised BT for, among other things, letting Indian call handlers use their own names instead of phoney English ones. Discouraging employees from lying seems a pretty modest achievement, and even that is disputed by the Communication Workers Union, which called the report "eyewash".\par \par \uc2 Companies whose activities are inherently destructive have special problems, reflected in the agonised vagueness of a statement on the CSR web pages of British American Tobacco. "Strong emotions . . . can surround our products, but we think [that] gets in the way of practical progress," BAT blathers, concluding desperately: "Do you think a tobacco company can be socially responsible? We welcome your view, and your thoughts on whether we are moving in the right direction." Talk about groping in the dark for a light switch.\par \par \uc2 Shell, whose products contribute to climate change, does a better job of owning up and proposing alternatives, though it was the prospect of falling revenues, not rising sea temperatures, that made its shares collapse recently. Other businesses simply ignore tricky issues. Barclays' 2002 CSR report details how many personal computers it junked, but not how much it lent to arms makers. And I could find no reference in Tesco's 2003 CSR report to the thousands of small shopkeepers put out of business by the expansion of supermarkets.\par \par \uc2 Despite such omissions, producing a CSR report is portrayed as a symbol of virtue, with one CSR consultancy last year "outing" FTSE 100 companies that had not published one. Associated British Foods and Hays, two of those named, told me they had put the information in their annual reports, saving several stands of Finnish pines from the pulp mill.\par \par \uc2 Another CSR consultancy, Article 13, recently made the dismaying claim that just 10 out of 350 of Britain's largest quoted companies had set up social or environmental programmes. But Paul Toyne, a director, told me Article 13 had "good evidence" only for a sample of 40 companies. The figure of 350, he said, had been "good for grabbing the headlines, but you need to take it with a pinch of salt".\par \par \uc2 That is how I prefer to take all CSR. So does Stephen Tindale, director of Greenpeace, the environmental campaign group, who says: "Businesses are businesses. They make money, are answerable to shareholders and should not pretend otherwise." Professor Andrew Oswald, a Warwick University economist, says: "Firms should maximise profits, with ethical goals as a secondary aim." And despite hype about CSR permeating all aspects of a company's operations, that, thankfully, is what they are mostly doing.\par \par \uc2 jonathan.guthrie@ft.com \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 ccsr : \uc2 Corporate Social Responsibility | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trow