 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b SN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Financial Times (FT.Com)\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b SC\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 FTCOM\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LA\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (c) 2004 The Financial Times Limited. All rights reserved \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Do investors or analysts need to get out of bed? I wondered this on Monday morning as I watched a live 'webcast' of a press conference announcing the merger of Sanofi-Synthelabo and Aventis. It's an impressive use of the web - but are companies really giving shareholders all they can on their bedside computer screens?\par \par \uc2 Having spent much time looking at online investor relations sections, I can say with certainty that I don't know. Either some companies are approaching perfection, and the rest will catch up in due course. Or everyone is running out of ideas, and no one knows how to make the next great leap forward.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 All I would say is that development is slowing, and converging on much the same model. It is now possible to describe the 'perfect' online site and measure all others against it. Except, of course, that I have no way of knowing it is perfect: it is just where the art has got to so far.\par \par \uc2 So what does it consist of, this perfection? Well, webcasts are a big feature. I know analysts find them useful and I can see why. The intriguing thing is that small investors can tap into previously closed conference calls or press conferences, and become dangerously well-informed. I wonder if the Eurotunnel rebels bugged the professionals in this way when planning their coup?\par \par \uc2 The webcast I watched on Sanofi-Synthelabo's site ( {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.sanofi-synthelabo.com"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 www.sanofi-synthelabo.com}}}\uc2 ) was a one-off special to announce the merger. Given the presumably short notice, it was impressively done. At first I struggled with the French version, then noticed an English link and found I could get not only a simultaneous translation but also my own set of downloadable slides.\par \par \uc2 Planned presentations should be slicker, and they often are. British companies often have the most sophisticated affairs - Smiths Group ( {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.smiths-group.com"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 www.smiths-group.com}}}\uc2 ), for example, offers a choice of audio or video, synchronised slides presentations and an option to download the slides either in PDF or Powerpoint format. The sophistication here is not in the clever technology, but in the choice. A big issue is whether people working in companies are allowed to watch video, or even listen to audio, because the software can be blocked by the company 'firewall'. It is interesting that Smiths has only recently started offering Powerpoint - this is an innovation based on common sense (everyone has Powerpoint software), rather than technology.\par \par \uc2 Tweaks such as this mark out the best from the not quite so good. Another simple idea is a webcast reminder ( {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.chevrontexaco.com"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 www.chevrontexaco.com}}}\uc2 , for example). Fill in your details, and you will be e-mailed before the event. Basic, but it works.\par \par \uc2 Then there are the technological refinements. Nordic companies have taken stock charts to a high art. Look at Stora Enso's ( {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.storaenso.com"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 www.storaenso.com}}}\uc2 ). Choose which of three exchanges you want to monitor, adjust the time period, select the indices and competitors you want to compare with, and have fun watching the numbers dance as you move your cursor across the chart. That is the Java version. If you are stuck behind a firewall, you may have to make do with the HTML (web) version. But it's still good.\par \par \uc2 Some other interesting techno-enhancements. Novartis ( {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.novartis.com"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 www.novartis.com}}}\uc2 ) offers analysts a Virtual Body, where they can click on a rather ghoulish figure to see which products treat which part of it, and the revenues they generate. (The direct link seems to have vanished, but you can still find it with the search engine.) Still in pharmaceuticals, look at Novo Nordisk ( {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.novonordisk.com"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 www.novonordisk.com}}}\uc2 ) and its interactive research and development pipeline. On an altogether grander scale, seek out the Interactive Analyst at BP ( {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.bp.com"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 www.bp.com}}}\uc2 ). This is an astonishing charting tool that allows analysts or researchers to build up charts using five years' worth of financial and operating data - then download them as pictures or Excel files.\par \par \uc2 But all of these are refinements on a theme, even if some are rather remarkable. Are there ways in which investor relations websites can really move on? I can think of two possibilities, one prosaic, one far-reaching.\par \par \uc2 The prosaic one is for companies to realise that they have two completely different type of shareholder. The needs of the analyst/institutional investors and those of the individual shareholder have little in common, yet they are usually served from the same jumbled shop. It is as though the same showroom sold diamonds and baked beans. You want to schmooze the diamond buyers (analysts) to the max, while encouraging grocery shoppers (private shareholders) to help themselves without bothering your sales people. While companies often have a brief 'shareholders' section few, at least in Europe, offer them their own showroom. Abbey ( {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.abbeynational.com"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 www.abbeynational.com}}}\uc2 ) is one of those few.\par \par \uc2 A little more far-reaching is the idea that IR sections could disappear. BP has a prominent banner on its IR home page encouraging visitors to visit its new \b \highlight22\uc2 Environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and Society website. "Is sustainability a fundamental prerequisite of long-term financial success?" it asks. Good question. It also raises the question of whether the \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  material should be inside the IR site. If so, what about the product and services material? Analysts have to look at that too. Then they should be able to see all the news and features that journalists are treated to. The point is that almost everything on a website is relevant to the serious investor or analyst, so why not have a small area where they can find the strictly financial material, and otherwise let them roam where they will? Similar arguments, incidentally, can be made about media sections, but that must be another story.\par \par \uc2 I'm not saying I am right about this, but I do have the feeling that unless some radical ideas are thrown around, online investor relations will quite soon stop evolving. And that, as Mr Darwin has explained, would be a bad thing.\par \par \uc2 David Bowen is a website effectiveness consultant for Bowen Craggs &Co ( {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.bowencraggs.com"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 www.bowencraggs.com}}}\uc2 ) \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widc