e misguided moral code of corporate responsibility", April 20) set out to rubbish the \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  movement but ends up making the business case for corporate responsibility when he stated that "even a curmudgeon like me believes that companies should treat their employees well and avoid damaging the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the communities where they operate. It will generally make them more profitable."\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Mr Guthrie went on to object to the pressure on companies to document their ethical record through reporting and ranking exercises. The demands, however, come not so much from non-governmental organisations and CSR consultants but increasingly from customers and institutional investors - the Association of British Insurers, US pension funds such as TIAA-CREF (Teachers Insurance and Annuity Association/College Retirement Equities Fund), or the Carbon Disclosure Project, a coalition of companies and important lenders concerned about the financial consequences of climate change.\par \par \uc2 Investors take CSR seriously because corporate responsibility and risk management, including risks to reputation, are inextricably linked and have an impact on shareholder value.\par \par \uc2 Mr Guthrie cited an economist's view that companies "should maximise profits with ethical goals as a secondary aim". How many more corporate scandals will it take to learn the lesson that maximising profits at the e