\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LA\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (Copyright (c) 2004, Dow Jones & Company, Inc.) \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Tokyo -- INVESTING IN companies that incorporate responsible social and environmental policies is a hot concept in the U.S. and Europe. In fact, an entire sector of the global fund-management industry has developed around the idea that good corporate citizenship is good business, and rewarding for investors.\par \par \uc2 Now, that trend is starting to gain traction in Japan as a series of corporate scandals spurs some investors to seek out socially responsible companies. Two stocks, Canon and Sompo Japan Insurance, look especially well positioned to benefit as a result.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Fund-management firms clearly see a future in the socially responsible investing movement. Japan's STB Asset Management set up its Japanese-equity Good Company investment trust in December. Last month, Nomura Asset Management established the Nomura Global SRI 100, which invests in companies from around the world that are included in the FTSE4Good Global 100 Index. Also last month, Daiwa Asset Management set up the Japanese-equity Daiwa SRI Fund.\par \par \uc2 The new Morningstar Socially Responsible Investment Index, meanwhile, tracks the share performance of select Japanese companies based on their commitment to society, such as environmental care. In addition, four global stock indexes that track socially responsible companies include Japanese stocks: the FTSE4Good Global Index, the FTSE4Good Global 100 Index, the Dow Jones Sustainability World Index and the Ethibel Sustainability Index Global.\par \par \uc2 Canon is the only Japanese company selected by all of the five indexes that track this sector. The maker of printers and cameras is known for promoting product recycling and using environmentally friendly substances in its products. From June 2001 to May 2004, Canon's share price rose 16%, outperforming the Topix index of all the Tokyo Stock Exchange's first-section shares, which fell 13% during the three-year period.\par \par \uc2 Sompo Japan, an insurance company created in July 2002 by the merger of Yasuda Fire &Marine Insurance and Nissan Fire &Marine Insurance, was chosen by four of the five indexes. The company offers \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 -related insurance products, such as car-insurance plans that offer a discount to drivers of "green" cars, and an "eco fund" -- an investment trust that tracks environmentally friendly companies. Its shares have risen 31% from July 2002 to May 2004. That beat the Topix's 11% rise during the same period. Tokyo research firm IntegreX, which rates companies on how socially responsible they are, also ranks Sompo Japan tops among publicly traded Japanese companies.\par \par \uc2 Corporate responsibility isn't the only reason shares of Canon and Sompo Japan are rising. Canon's net profit has more than doubled during the past three years, while Sompo Japan posted net profit of 55.09 billion yen ($503.2 million) for the year ended March 31, reversing a year-earlier net loss of 40.99 billion yen.\par \par \uc2 Still, the stamp of approval from socially responsible investing indexes and research firms is appealing to an increasing number of investment trusts and corporate pension funds these days.\par \par \uc2 More companies in Japan are starting to cater to socially responsible investment funds. In a bid to improve their corporate-brand image, Sony Corp., Ricoh Co. and Matsushita Electric Industrial Co., among others, last year set up \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social\b0 \highlight\uc2 -\b \highlight22\uc2 responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  divisions to promote awareness among investors and consumers about their contributions to society and to the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 A Sony spokeswoman said the company's new division also keeps a tab on chemical substances used in each product it makes.\par \par \uc2 ---\par \par \uc2 Yesterday's Market Activity\par \par \uc2 Overall, the Dow Jones World Stock Index rose 0.38%, or 0.73, to 190.62. Excluding the U.S., the index rose 0.63%, or 0.92, to 147.74.\par \par \uc2 In TOKYO, the Nikkei Stock Average rose 2.2%, or 254.02 points, to 11641.72, more than recouping declines during the preceding three days. Seiko Epson rose 4.0% to 3,660 yen and Advantest rose 3.4% to 7,090 yen. Asahi Glass rose 2.7% to 1,100 yen and Pioneer added 2.8% to 2,740 yen. These issues have faced heavy selling lately because of worries that a rise in electronic-parts inventories and a possible slowdown in product demand may hurt their earnings this year.\par \par \uc2 In LONDON, the FTSE 100 Index rose 0.7%, or 32.50 points, to 4491.10. Haulier Tibbett &Britten climbed 14.0% to 666.5 pence after contract-logistics provider Exel launched a recommended 668 pence-a-share takeover offer. Exel rose 1.3% to 714.5 pence. Lloyds TSB Group was up 0.4% at 438.25 pence.\par \par \uc2 In FRANKFURT, the Xetra DAX Index rose 0.4%, or 15.94 points, to 4003.24. Commerzbank unit Comdirect Bank said it has agreed to sell its United Kingdom subsidiary to a unit of Lloyds TSB Group for 16.5 million euros. Comdirect fell 0.5% to 7.01 euros, Commerzbank was up 2.1% at 14.59 euros.\par \par \uc2 --- \par \par \uc2 \f2 \par                                     MSCI Indexes \par  \par                                                        % CHG \par                            JUN 15         JUN 14     FROM 12/03 \par  \par U.S. ..................... 1060.3         1053.8        +1.4 \par Britain .................. 1346.3         1339.3        -0.2 \par Canada ................... 1038.4         1024.4        +1.8 \par Japan ....................  692.7          696.6        +8.7 \par France ................... 1208.1         1196.7        +3.6 \par Germany ..................  489.4          484.9        -0.5 \par Hong Kong ................ 6257.4         6275.3        -1.3 \par Switzerland ..............  742.8          738.0        +4.0 \par Australia ................  688.5          690.6        +5.0 \par World Index .............. 1048.3      