 Monetary Fund since June 7, begins a visit to Japan, China, Singapore and Vietnam. Mr Rato will discuss each country's economic outlook and regional issues in meetings with leaders and senior government officials.\par \par \uc2 ACP meets in 'risky world' Maputo, Mozambique, hosts the fourth African, Caribbean and Pacific summit (to June 24). Reflecting the conference theme, "Together, shaping our future!", the host, Joaquim Chissano, president, in a message to heads of state and government from 70 countries, said the ACP was positioning itself on the global geopolitical scene as a united, strong and open group buoyed by a real concern to facilitate fair and global solutions in an increasingly unique but risky world.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 A better life The United Nations population fund, whose executive board meets in Geneva this week, releases the results of a global survey on progress during the past 10 years in implementing decisions of the 1994 Cairo world conference on population and development. Issues covered include maternal mortality, gender equality and access to reproductive health services, including family planning and sexual health.\par \par \uc2 Baltic Sea summit Prime ministers from Baltic Sea states meet in Laulasmaa, Estonia, to discuss sustainable development, maritime safety, marine \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  protection and human trafficking in the region. Members are Denmark, Estonia, Finland, Germany, Iceland, Latvia, Lithuania, Norway, Poland, Russia and Sweden.\par \par \uc2 Outcomes, not systems The International Organisation for Standardisation begins a two-day conference in Geneva on the possible development of Iso standards for \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Iso's series of management standards already covers issues such as environmental management, but critics disparage the focus on systems rather than outcomes.\par \par \uc2 FT Reports Management - focusing on corporate relationships Financial Training - skills move to the top of the agenda\par \par \uc2 TUESDAY 22\par \par \uc2 Philippine peace talks Talks resume in Oslo between the Philippine government and communist rebels aimed at ending the 35-year insurgency in that country (to June 25). Negotiations will focus on a ceasefire and the reconciliation of differences on issues such as land rights and power sharing. Norway is brokering the talks to end Asia's longest rebellion in which thousands have died.\par \par \uc2 Killing development Oxfam, Amnesty International and the International Action Network on Small Arms will publishGuns or Growth?, a report for the Control Arms campaign showing the impact of arms sales on development. It will reveal how arms-exporting governments are breaking their own promises to assess the sale of arms against the impact on poverty.\par \par \uc2 East meets west Junichiro Koizumi, Japanese prime minister, meets Bertie Ahern, Irish president of the European Union, and Romano Prodi, president of the European Commission, in Tokyo. In the first summit since EU enlargement, they will discuss strategic partnerships, political and economic relations and the international situation.\par \par \uc2 Not so sweet taxes The dispute settlement body of the World Trade Organisation meets in Geneva to consider two panel requests. The US seeks an investigation into Mexico's taxes on soft drinks sweetened with high fructose corn syrup, a big US export to Mexico, rather than sugar. Canada wants an inquiry into penal US tariffs on Canadian wheat used for bread-making.\par \par \uc2 FT Reports Greece - the challenge of hosting the Olympics Slovenia - new EU member faces budget dilemmas\par \par \uc2 WEDNESDAY 23\par \par \uc2 More anti-nuclear talking The third round of the six-party talks on North Korea's nuclear capability resumes in Beijing. The US demands that Pyongyang halt its nuclear programme while North Korea seeks security guarantees and aid. Previous talks have made little progress.\par \par \uc2 America's green option US Greens party holds its presidential nominating convention in Milwaukee, Wisconsin (to June 28). Ralph Nader, candidate in the most recent election, has formally withdrawn, but there is a movement to draft him and he has collected delegate commitments in state primaries.\par \par \uc2 FT Reports FT-IT Review - phishing for passwords India: Investment - ability to compete inspires confidence (Asia only)\par \par \uc2 THURSDAY 24\par \par \uc2 Palestinian summer The International Solidarity Movement launches "Freedom summer Palestine 2004", a campaign aimed at rallying international support for an independent Palestinian state. Over 56 days it will denounce alleged abuses by Israel in the 56 years since the Jewish state was created. On the day before the campaign, Saeb Erekat, the Palestinian chief negotiator, is to meet Colin Powell, US secretary of state, in Washington to discuss Israel's plans to evacuate the Gaza Strip and expand Jewish settlements in the West Bank.\par \par \uc2 Global business compact Kofi Annan, United Nations secretary-general, convenes the Global Compact Leaders summit in New York, billed as the largest gathering yet of business leaders, government officials and civil representatives on the topic of global corporate responsibility. Launched by Mr Annan in 2000, the global compact includes more than 1,400 companies.\par \par \uc2 FT Report Business and Development - Sowing seeds of understanding\par \par \uc2 FRIDAY 25\par \par \uc2 Bush in County Clare A European Union-US summit takes place in Dromoland Castle, Co Clare, Ireland (to June 26). George W.Bush, US president, will attend. His host, Bertie Ahern, the Irish prime minister, said he was determined to strengthen transatlantic ties by highlighting the positive aspects of the relationship. He listed counter-terrorism, non-proliferation, Afghanistan and the Balkans as examples of working together.\par \par \uc2 Top film hits US screens Michael Moore's controversial documentary on business links between two generations of the\par \par \uc2 Bush and bin Laden families, Fahrenheit 9/11, is due to open in more than 1,000 US cinemas. The film won the Palme d'Or at the Cannes film festival.\par \par \uc2 Algeria aims for WTO The working party negotiating Algeria's accession to the World Trade Organisation meets in Geneva. Negotiations, which began in 1996, still have some way to go.\par \par \uc2 SUNDAY 27\par \par \uc2 Bush in Turkish talks George W. Bush, US president, on an official visit to Turkey, will hold talks with Turkish leaders, including Recep Tayyip Erdogan, prime minister. They will discuss Turkish support of the greater Middle East initiative, US "privileges" granted on Turkish soil and Turkish help in Afghanistan and Iraq under Nato's umbrella. The Nato summit begins in Istanbul tomorrow.\par \par \uc2 China on show in London The China Expo 2004 Trade and Investment Fair begins at Earls Court exhibition centre, London. Chinese manufacturers, investors and government agencies will display what the booming economic giant has to offer. The event, aimed at fostering trade with the UK and Europe, expects 40,000 visitors.\par \par \uc2 Compiled by Denis Herbstein denis.herbstein@ft.com \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trle