ft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The other is the development world: horrified that much of the planet remains so poor but chastened by decades of failed aid programmes and misguided experiments in social redistribution.\par \par \uc2 Both groups have traditionally viewed each other with mistrust, if not overt hostility. Many in the development world believed private industry had little interest in social justice and limited relevance to governments' efforts to provide basic services.\par \par \uc2 Corporations dismissed the development crowd as woolly-headed do-gooders with a taste for prescriptive measures but little understanding of what made economies tick.\par \par \uc2 At the end of the 1990s, this tension came to a new head when development activists sparked riots in the industrialised countries' heartlands. Opposition to the inequities of an increasingly global marketplace became a cause celebre in the first world.\par \par \uc2 At the same time, communities in the developing world, increasingly empowered by new political freedom and better communications, discovered new tools to organise and express their concerns.\par \par \uc2 Half a decade later those battles have given way to war and terror in the daily headlines. But under the radar, in places like the United Nations, their legacy is reaping a surprising result. Little by little, the former adversaries have begun to come together, and concede that each side may have a point.\par \par \uc2 Faced with the prospect of local unrest and global campaigns, increasing numbers of business leaders have sought new ways of bringing their critics on board. Why fight with communities when there is money to be made? There might even be new markets in catering for the demands of the poor.\par \par \uc2 Those business leaders who have started to play by more ethical rules have acquired an interest in seeing others do the same. Some dare to hope that if new standards are widely adopted, the world might even become a safer place for them.\par \par \uc2 "It's a security issue, for sure," says William Parrett, chief executive officer of Deloitte. "It's also a business issue; crucial to the sustainability of the capital markets system. To bolster the rule of law, multinational companies must engage in ethical behaviour that promotes greater economic opportunity. Otherwise the divide between those who have and those who don't will continue to grow and provide fertile ground for the seeds of hatred and unrest."\par \par \uc2 "If we're an integral part of the solution, people want you to be successful," says Pfizer CEO Hank McKinnel. "The trick is picking the priorities."\par \par \uc2 At the same time the development world has also started to change. Increasing numbers of governments, development economists and non-governmental organisations are admitting that aid is not enough. Neither, they acknowledge, is macro-economic reform.\par \par \uc2 Many are coming to the conclusion that, while far from perfect, - and constant oversight is needed - only private enterprise has the energy, the capacity to mobilise finance and inventiveness to make life better for the world's poor.\par \par \uc2 The UN's Commission on the Private Sector and Development recently released a report that, a few hundred years after Adam Smith came to a similar conclusion, finally acknowledged that "the savings, investment and innovation that lead to development are undertaken largely by private individuals, corporations and communities."\par \par \uc2 It concluded that developing countries' governments must find better ways to foster private industry, especially the forgotten medium-sized enterprises. While obvious to many, it marked the culmination of a remarkable change of heart for the UN.\par \par \uc2 The report may also herald a new phase in development policy after the macro-economic reforms of the 1990s failed to reap the hoped-for results. "A lot of developing country governments have spent the last 10 years restructuring their public sectors: and suddenly are looking over the edge of the road," says Mark Malloch Brown, head of the UN Development Programme.\par \par \uc2 "What's missing is jobs and growth. There is no sign of an emerging tax base to sustain services in the future. Why not? There's a remarkably thin middle." The UNDP and others believe that multinationals can play a crucial role in fostering this "middle", the small and medium enterprises, through support for local suppliers - with the added benefit that local people may show an interest in seeing them stick around.\par \par \uc2 This coming together of communities has created an extraordinary opportunity. "There is a confluence of interests," says Nancy Birdsall, president of the Centre for Global Development. "It's a very exciting time: there is a grand convergence," agrees Joseph O'Keefe, from the International Finance Corporation.\par \par \uc2 "Development institutions and developing countries are beginning to recognise the basic structure of global development finance is probably not going to change. Public sector development assistance is between Dollars 50bn and Dollars 60bn; while the private sector offers between Dollars 200bn and Dollars 300bn in cross-border flows."\par \par \uc2 At the same time, he says, "business is waking up to the development agenda, recognising it has a vested interest in doing things a different way and better. These are the markets where they are going to see the fastest growth over the coming decades."\par \par \uc2 CK Prahalad, the management expert, has caught the wave with his new book: The Fortune at the Bottom of the Pyramid" . He claims it is time for businessmen to start thinking about poverty in a totally different way: as an opportunity rather than a problem, a market rather than a drain on resources.\par \par \uc2 "While large firms and multinational corporations may have exploited the poor in some cases, the greatest harm they may have done is to ignore them," he writes.\par \par \uc2 With the right business solutions, which require a significant rethink of developed world business models, he says there is a huge market - Dollars 14,000bn in public-private partnership dollars - to be tapped.\par \par \uc2 Big companies can act as catalytic nodes for smaller ones. And in the process, Mr Prahalad believes, the poor will win respect, dignity and the power of choice.\par \par \uc2 In essence, he argues, we must stop seeing the poor as wards of the state, but as fertile consumers, if only the right models can be found to address their needs.\par \par \uc2 Nonetheless, the reconciliation is far from complete. Many development organisations are deeply sceptical of the apparent conversion of business, and fear that the fast-emerging fields of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 , public-private partnerships and the like is little more than a public relations exercise. Many still believe the only way to bring business in line is through the establishment of global rules, such as are being discussed in Geneva.\par \par \uc2 On the other side of the coin, many businesses are wary of the new risks that acknowledging their responsibilities, through reporting on their social and environmental impacts, may incur: as witnessed in recent litigation against claims by Nike.\par \par \uc2 Some NGOs also believe that big companies should not meddle in the provision of health care and education, jobs better undertaken by the state.\par \par \uc2 Those in favour of greater private participation insist there is no intention for the private sector to replace the state, but say it can act as a provider of good ideas, innovative models, and as a catalyst for better public policy.\par \par \uc2 No one said it would be easy. "This is not going to be a cake-walk," says Mr Prahalad. At the end of the day, however, he and an increasing number of people have come to a shared conclusion. "Large scale entrepreneurship is at the heart of the solution to poverty. The poor must become consumers. Poverty reduction can result from developing a market around the poor." \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 ccsr : \uc2 Corporate Social Responsibility | gdev : \uc2 Development/Humanitarian Aid | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | gcat : \uc2 Political/General News | gdip : \uc2 International Relations | gpir : \uc2 Politics/International Relations | gwelf : \uc2 Welfare/Social Services | c13 : \uc2 Regulation/Government Policy | gcom : \uc2 Society/Community/Work\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RE\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 uk : \uc2 United Kingdom | eecz : \uc2 European Union Countries | eurz : \uc2 Europe | weurz : \uc2 Western Europe\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intb