t\rin0\lin0 \uc2 As Germany's leading consumer product guide introduces ethical criteria, Hugh Williamson looks at the issues of ranking. German shoppers are in for a surprise. Later this year when they open Test, the country's leading guide to consumer products, they will not only find the usual lists of the best cookers or camping equipment ranked by value for money and ease of use. They will also be presented with products assessed on new criteria - whether the practices used in their production comply with international social and labour standards, and whether they are good or bad for the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 While the first three pilot tests containing the extra information appear unspectacular - covering all-weather jackets, washing powder and salmon - the significance of their inclusion in a magazine that is the buying bible for many German households is obvious. For the first time, at least in Germany, issues that companies are tackling under the broad banner of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  are finding their way out of the battleground between business and campaign groups and into the product pages of a mainstream consumer magazine.\par \par \uc2 Stiftung Warentest, the consumer organisation that publishes Test, stirred controversy when it decided to include the extra information - not least because, with sales of 650,000 a month, the magazine has real impact on consumer choices.\par \par \uc2 "Depending where you stand, our initiative has created either hope or fear that these social and environmental issues will gain extra weight in society if a major player such as Stiftung Warentest addresses them in a more concerted way," says Holger Brackemann, SWT research co-ordinator.\par \par \uc2 SWT has in fact been slower than its European counterparts to make the link between CSR issues and product tests. Consumer magazines in about 10 countries have already published tests that include social, labour and environmental criteria, according to Andrea Klag of the London-based International Consumer Research and Testing organisation that co-ordinates product tests for consumer magazines.\par \par \uc2 Indeed Rob Harrison, editor of the UK's Ethical Consumer magazine, sees a "general trend among mainstream consumer groups around the world to satisfy the growing consumer appetite for information on ethical issues".*\par \par \uc2 Which?, the UK consumer magazine, last year included CSR criteria in tests on running shoes and mobile phones, while Consumentenbond, the Netherlands' main consumer association, has published 20 reports containing CSR information.\par \par \uc2 This trend offers new opportunities for consumers to make well-informed choices, but also creates challenges such as how to assess the CSR-related qualities of a product and how such assessments should be presented to consumers. Although working from different starting points, companies, consumer magazines and non-governmental organisations all admit these challenges will take time and effort to overcome.\par \par \uc2 "We are still in the learning phase in terms of methodologies, in getting sufficient data from companies, and on whether consumers can really use this extra information," says Jane O'Brien, head of research at Which?, who co-ordinated the magazine's adoption of CSR criteria.\par \par \uc2 Mr Brackemann says that SWT's decision was consumer-driven. "It is clear from surveys that consumers are increasingly interested in social and environmental issues, so we are responding to that. Products are becoming more similar in terms of quality, so consumers are looking for other ways of making purchasing choices."\par \par \uc2 The first test with CSR criteria will be on all-weather jackets - a good choice, according to SWT, as these are made not in Germany but in eastern Europe and south-east Asia, where CSR standards are often lower.\par \par \uc2 SWT has prepared a 20-page questionnaire with 39 criteria to be sent to companies with jackets in the main product test. The questions cover a company's social, employment and environmental policies, its relations with suppliers, and whether monitoring structures exist to check whether policies are being properly implemented on the ground.\par \par \uc2 The information from companies will be supplemented with data from non-governmental organisations and the media, and from auditing companies commissioned by SWT to run independent checks on what the company has said. The compiled data will not be included in the price and quality information in the traditional rankings, but will be presented, without explicit gradings, on a separate page, thus avoiding a direct link - feared by some companies - between the two aspects.\par \par \uc2 Mr Brackemann stresses that, as far as possible, the CSR criteria will focus on the production processes behind specific products, not on the companies that make them, as a company such as Siemens with many different products may perform differently on telephones than on refrigerators.\par \par \uc2 The BDI, Germany's main industry federation, opposes SWT's move because of the methodological difficulties in gathering and presenting the data in a balanced way. This could lead to "market distortion", says Marie Luise Eul, the BDI's environmental policy expert. "We have high social standards in Germany, but smaller companies in particular are unaware what '\b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 ' means and what counts as (CSR)."\par \par \uc2 In contrast, Heinz-Dieter Koeppe, director of environmental and social policy at retailer KarstadtQuelle, says the issue has become "how - and not whether - such tests (with CSR criteria) are done".\par \par \uc2 Like many companies with a track record of working on CSR issues, he says consumer magazines should take a company-specific - not product-specific - approach, so that the "broad, ongoing process of working with suppliers and stakeholders" on CSR can be better reflected. If not, there is a danger that "we supply lots of information and another company gives no information, and we both end up getting criticised."\par \par \uc2 For this reason it is very important that SWT is explicit and transparent about the basis on which it makes judgments, he adds.\par \par \uc2 Mr Brackemann says the focus will be "as much on (CSR) policies . . . as on the realities on the ground of how products are made".\par \par \uc2 Other consumer magazines have been through similar debates, and their experiences highlight three main challenges ahead. First, the selection of products to test is problematic. Ms O'Brien at Which? says opinions vary between focusing on products popular with consumers, such as mobile phones, or on areas where it is well known that CSR standards are low, such as among banana producers.\par \par \uc2 Second, complex issues involved in obtaining reliable and verifiable information from companies remain unresolved. Consumentenbond has found that many companies have no procedures to gather CSR information in their own companies, let alone from the many layers of suppliers they use.\par \par \uc2 Even if procedures exist, many companies are undecided on whether to co- operate, says Melanie Peters, Consumentenbond's CSR expert. "Companies tell governments that they are against regulation on CSR, but then they are also unwilling to present information on a voluntary basis. It's our impression that they are still weighing up whether to inform consumers or not. They don't know if transparency is helping them or hurting them."\par \par \uc2 Third, magazines stress the problem of balancing the need to report transparently and in detail on the information gathered on the one hand, with consumers' requirements for simple, understandable guidance on the other.\par \par \uc2 Perhaps surprisingly, the Clean Clothes Campaign, an NGO that lobbies clothing retailers to improve working conditions in their suppliers, says magazines should avoid presenting "over-simplified" information in the form of rankings or score-cards. Ineke Zeldenrust, spokeswoman, says: "The issues are complex, and it is dangerous to present snapshots of company practices that change over time. Fake consumer advice is of no use to anyone."\par \par \uc2 Mr Brackemann says SWT and other publishers will not be put off by these problems, and notes that Consumentenbond has the goal of including CSR criteria in half its product tests by late 2005. It appears this year's surprises for German shoppers will soon become their standard fare.\par \par \uc2 * Rob Harrison, '\b \highlight22\uc2 Corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the consumer movement', in Consumer Policy Review, July 2003 \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 iadv : \uc2 Advertising/Public Relations/Marketing\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \