 bid for Marks and Spencer by Philip Green would threaten its reputation as a responsible retailer, Business in the Community, the business-led campaign for corporate responsibility, has claimed.\par \par \uc2 Stuart Rose, the new chief executive who is defending M&S against Mr Green, collected the company of the year award for M&S at the BITC's annual Awards for Excellence last night. The retailer was praised for its "outstanding" impact on society in areas such as sustainable food production and labour standards among suppliers.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 "These aren't values by which Philip Green runs the business," said Julia Cleverdon, BITC chief executive, before the ceremony. "I think these values will go if he takes over and takes it private."\par \par \uc2 The charge came as the Takeover Panel gave Mr Green a month to make a formal bid or walk away for six months. The ultimatum - which followed a request from M&S - comes more than five weeks after Mr Green announced his intention to bid.\par \par \uc2 He has since put forward two proposals - the most recent worth "not less than" 370p-a-share in cash. M&S rejected both and Mr Green has yet to table a formal bid. The shares stood at 360p last night.\par \par \uc2 The Panel had issued 12 "put up or shut up" statements since the start of 2002. In all but three cases, the potential bidder walked away. Mr Green said the deadline made no difference. "So what? What does it change?" he said. His ability to bid depended on obtaining information about the M&S pension scheme, he added. Mr Green has sought a meeting with the trustees.\par \par \uc2 The deadline was welcomed by Martin Cholwill, UK equity fund manager at Axa Investment Managers, a top-10 M&S shareholder. "We've been in the middle of a phoney war for a while," he said.\par \par \uc2 David Varney, chairman of BITC, acknowledged the award would be controversial but said: "We think (corporate responsibility) is an important ingredient of a successful business. If you fall short on something else, it doesn't have the capacity to compensate. But it can speed your recovery if you have a problem." Mr Varney is also chairman of MMO,the mobile operator, where Paul Myners, M&S's interim chairman, is a director.\par \par \uc2 Ms Cleverdon said: "Anybody looking at (M&S) would discover there are a lot of values in there which had added to the financial value.\par \par \uc2 "You would destroy that at your peril." By contrast with Mr Green, Mr Rose had a record of doing "the things which help to build stronger values among employees, the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and communities", she added. .\par \par \uc2 Mr Rose told the FT he was committed to \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 . "I hope to be here, and if I am here, it will be part of the business."\par \par \uc2 Mark Goyder, director of Tomorrow's Company, business think-tank, and one of the judges of the top award, organised in association with the Financial Times and the Department of Trade and Industry, challenged the future leaders of M&S to maintain its record of responsible behaviour or return the award.\par \par \uc2 Additional reporting by Clay Harris \{i)Lex, Page 18 Lombard, Page 20 BITC awards, separate section Background, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.ft.com/marks"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 www.ft.com/marks}}}\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clve