I planned to write my column this week on the devaluation of the idea of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 , one of them told me that the idea could not be devalued because it was meaningless.\par \par \uc2 I, in turn, posed the following question: were German companies justified in using slave labour during the Nazi period, and if not why not? I did not receive a reply.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 It is quite right that we hold companies to a higher standard than simply obeying the law. As my question to my colleague suggested, not everything that is lawful in a particular society at a particular time is morally acceptable. We expect companies to adhere to certain standards of behaviour towards their employees, customers and the societies in which they operate.\par \par \uc2 When companies fall below those standards, they damage support for capitalism itself. South African companies' poor treatment of black workers during the apartheid years turned millions into communists, or at least deeply suspicious anti-capitalists, which many still are.\par \par \uc2 I do not think it is sufficient to argue that neither of the two societies I mentioned was a democracy, and that different rules should apply when voters can campaign for laws to curb objectionable activities. Most large companies from democratic countries operate in undemocratic ones too; that is where some of their most controversial practices take place.\par \par \uc2 So I am all for \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 , but I am equally aware that others are not. This is not because the objectors are unethical (my colleague is a paragon of decency), but because they think it is wrong to expect managers to do something as unmeasurable as help society, which is best served when companies make profits and distribute dividends to their shareholders.\par \par \uc2 I am also aware that many executives who talk about how socially responsible their companies are do so only because it is expected of them. The battle for CSR has to be won in an \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  more hostile than many of its proponents appreciate, which is why I was deeply irritated by the decision of Business in the Community, the UK organisation, to give its most prestigious award this year to Marks and Spencer.\par \par \uc2 If you live outside the UK, you may be only dimly aware of M&S, which is part of its problem. The retailer has been unsuccessful outside Britain. It sold the American Brooks Brothers chain in 2001 for a third of the price it had paid for it 13 years previously. In the same year, it withdrew from continental Europe, its final day marked by mobs looting its store on Paris's Boulevard Haussmann.\par \par \uc2 M&S has not, in recent years, been particularly successful in its home market either. It is not a basket case - it made pre-tax profits in 2003-04 of Pounds 740m (Dollars 1.4bn) - but it has been struggling to hold on to its customers. Luc Vandevelde, its chairman at the time, said earlier this year that "the market share gains that we had hoped to achieve were not delivered." Mr Vandevelde has since left. The company ousted Roger Holmes, its chief executive, as part of a management revamp designed to repel a takeover approach from retail entrepreneur Philip Green, who abandoned his attempt last week.\par \par \uc2 There was a time when I barely owned an item of clothing that was not from M&S. But, along with much of middle-aged, middle-class Britain, I tired of the listless staff and the increasingly poorly made garments, and discovered that other retailers sold clothes too. I still pop into M&S from time to time. I tried a cheery "hello" on the man on the cash register at the M&S food store when I bought my post-swim snack the other morning, but he didn't reply.\par \par \uc2 Still, as Business in the Community said excitedly when it gave M&S its award (in association with the FT and the Department of Trade and Industry), the company has received plaudits from Greenpeace for ensuring its foods are free of genetically modified ingredients, from Friends of the Earth for its pesticide reduction and from the Marine Conservation Society for its responsible sourcing of fish. In its 42-page CSR report, M&S added that it had reduced the amount of peat it used to grow plants and flowers, in line with the wishes of the Royal Society for the Protection of Birds. The problem is that a company that fails to look after its customers will not be around for long enough to care for the birds and the fish.\par \par \uc2 Other chief executives will read M&S's CSR report, note that Mr Vandevelde, who signed it, is gone, and conclude that their time is better spent making a decent profit than reducing the amount of peat in their plants.\par \par \uc2 The argument that consumers will flock to companies whose approach to CSR they admire is not convincing, as M&S's poor sales demonstrate. Asked whether they are prepared to spend more on goods that do not spoil the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  or rely on sweatshop labour, the majority of consumers say "yes", but their behaviour tells a different story. Sales of fair trade goods and the like may be growing, but they are small. When it comes to spending their hard-earned cash, consumers are hard-headed.\par \par \uc2 That does not mean there is no business case for CSR. Salmonella in eggs and BSE in beef sent consumers scurrying to companies that could guarantee their food was free of it. The most impressive part of M&S's report is its account of how it traces the food it sells from "field to fork".\par \par \uc2 Companies need to know where their goods come from and how they are produced so that when the next scare occurs, they can explain to customers why they can still be trusted. CSR is best seen as the management of risk, as the avoidance of damage to the company's reputation. But it is no substitute for the avoidance of the larger risk: that customers may go elsewhere because the company's offering is not good enough. As models, we need companies whose risk management has made them commercially successful. CSR is only as sustainable as the companies that practise it. michael.skapinker@ft.com \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 ccsr : \uc2 Corporate Social Responsibility | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | gcat : \uc2 Political/General News | gcom : \uc2 Society/Community/Work | gethic : \uc2 Ethical Issues\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RE\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 uk : \uc2 United Kingdom | eecz : \uc2 European Union C