\li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 It may have lacked the fanfare and controversy of the Higgs report on non-executive directors, but the proposed operating and financial review also represents a step-change in a company's relationship with shareholders.\par \par \uc2 Draft regulations for the OFR, prepared by the Department of Trade and Industry, have been out for consultation since May, and the deadline or responses is Friday. The initiative builds on guidance from the Accounting Standards Board and takes in - some would say gold-plates - the Modernisation Directive from the European Union.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Although the tone of the debate has been gentlemanly, the OFR has provoked contrasting reactions. The Institute of Directors has previously expressed concern about "an insidious creep in the direction of the stakeholder model".\par \par \uc2 Patricia Peter, corporate governance executive at the IoD, is less alarmist about the present draft. She says the "bald regulations make it clear that the OFR is addressed to members", or shareholders. But she remains worried about the detailed guidance, which makes many references to other constituencies - \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , employees, the wider community. "The risk is that they could make unfounded claims."\par \par \uc2 At the other end of the spectrum is Mark Goyder, director of Tomorrow's Company, a business think-tank, who has been an advocate of the OFR concept for years. "The beauty of the OFR is that it will be a core document, with all the high-level indicators (of a company's performance) in one place." He likens it to the spinal column, with more detailed reports - on governance and remuneration, for instance - running off it.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, shareholders, at whom the OFR is aimed, are not all as gung-ho in their welcome as Patricia Hewitt, trade secretary, might like them to be. After all, in her foreword to the draft OFR she says it is "designed to give shareholders what they need".\par \par \uc2 Michelle Edkins, a corporate governance expert at Hermes, one of the UK's largest pension fund managers, says her organisation is "broadly in favour", but she wonders whether the initiative will be hijacked by the \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  camp. "We believe the focus should be on disclosure of issues that impact on a company's ability to generate shareholder returns."\par \par \uc2 The National Association of Pension Funds welcomes it but fears that companies will take "a mechanistic approach with resultant bland and boilerplate language.Rather the OFR will require much better use of clear language with the emphasis on quality rather than quantity of information."\par \par \uc2 The NAPF questions the tight timetable: the government proposes that the OFR should be implemented for the year beginning January 1 2005. It points to the importance of the ASB producing "timely and non-contentious guidance" and would countenance a year's delay.\par \par \uc2 So what is in the draft that has produced such a guarded welcome from some of the key beneficiaries?\par \par \uc2 According to schedule 7ZA, it "shall be a balanced and comprehensive analysis of": the company's development and performance in the past year; its position at the end of the year; the "main trends and factors" underlying those things and the ones likely to affect them in the future.\par \par \uc2 It should also include business objectives and strategies, and "the principal risks and uncertainties facing the company". The OFR enters sensitive territory in encouraging more forward-looking information. Some respondents would like to see "safe harbour" provisions to ease directors' legal liability and their inhibitions in discussing what will drive performance. Then there is optional information about employees, environmental matters, social and community issues.\par \par \uc2 These should feature "to the extent necessary to comply" with the requirement that the OFR include information "necessary for an understanding of the development . . ."\par \par \uc2 Apart from the difficulty of grasping what this means, these softer and more subjective issues are far harder to measure. Hence the spawning of reports on subjects such as human capital management. No wonder the NAPF is worried about the quantity of information.\par \par \uc2 The underlying point that makes many in business uneasy about the OFR is that producing it will be a statutory obligation for quoted companies - no, not those on the Alternative Investment Market, which is set to escape again.\par \par \uc2 The Combined Code is enforced on a "comply or explain" basis. Failure to comply with OFR rules, wilfully or by neglect, is an offence and the directors involved can be fined. This has led Hermes to ask whether it would deter quality people from joining boards.\par \par \uc2 Taken with the prescriptive nature of some guidelines, the legal force of the OFR may encourage companies to follow the same road map, limiting its usefulness in assessing individual strengths and weaknesses.\par \par \uc2 Charles Tilley, chief executive of the Chartered Institute of Management Accountants, says: "The real challenge facing the government and regulators is to ensure that the OFR is a bold document ... A company must ask itself 'what are the issues we are looking at at board level?'" If the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , for instance, is not an issue, it will not be on that agenda.\par \par \uc2 Another "huge challenge" is for directors to be bold. To do that, "they need to feel they are not going to be sued". Nevertheless, Mr Tilley, like Mark Goyder, is a believer. The theory is, as Mr Goyder puts it, that there is an unbroken link between the purpose, values and behaviour of a company and its financial performance.\par \par \uc2 If the OFR does lead to a better public assessment of what determines a company's success, then it will have proved that the Higgsian changes to the board have enhanced its output. Talking Head, Page 6 \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 20040802S203.016\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 c41 : \uc2 Management Issues | ccpgvn : \uc2 Corporate Governance/Investor Relations | c13 : \uc2 Regulation/Government Policy | c131 : \uc2 Regulatory Bodies | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\c