mes coming for some in the industry as international students switch focus. Times have been tough for business schools and their flagship programme, the full-time MBA.\par \par \uc2 Dwindling numbers of applicants for full-time programmes, an exacting job market, increased competition, a shortage of staff (or faculty), not to mention a complete overhaul of the continental European higher education system, have all taken their toll.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Although not as pummelled as their US counterparts, European schools suffered in the recent straitened economic times. Jobs were hard to come by and this, coupled with general criticism of the relevance of the MBA qualification, doubtless deterred potential candidates.\par \par \uc2 But the corner has been turned. According to the 2004 Corporate Recruiters Survey just published by the Graduate Management Admission Council (GMAC), corporate recruiters are now more optimistic about the economy.\par \par \uc2 A total of 1,300 recruiters representing 1,004 companies worldwide took part in the survey and of these only 50 per cent blame the economy for putting curbs on their hiring: two years ago this figure was 69 per cent.\par \par \uc2 "Clearly, the economic recovery is beginning to open up more opportunities for MBA graduates," says David Wilson, president of GMAC. "In fact, companies plan to hire more people for every job category we tracked. These results are very encouraging."\par \par \uc2 However, although there may be more jobs, US visa restrictions are still damping international students' enthusiasm for US business schools.\par \par \uc2 But while this is a negative for US schools, it is something of a bonus for European institutions.\par \par \uc2 Anecdotal evidence suggests that Middle Eastern students who might once have opted for a US management education are now looking to Europe to fulfil their MBA needs.\par \par \uc2 Moreover, some prospective students are turning away from the US because of the strength of sentiment against the Iraq war.\par \par \uc2 The net result is that European schools have a bigger pool in which to fish and the resulting increase in diversity enhances the European MBA experience.\par \par \uc2 But while cultural diversity is on the increase, the perennial problem of faculty shortage is once again causing concern.\par \par \uc2 Eric Cornuel, director general and chief executive officer of the Brussels-based European Foundation for Management Development, predicts that the dearth of faculty will reach catastrophic proportions.\par \par \uc2 In the US, he says, there will be a shortfall of as many as 2,500 professors within 10 years. While EFMD is still collating figures for Europe, Prof Cornuel is pessimistic.\par \par \uc2 He cites several reasons for the faculty crisis. In Europe, he says, where many business schools opened their doors in the late 1970s and 1980s, many respected faculty are now nearing retirement.\par \par \uc2 Furthermore, fewer graduates are opting for the PhD route. And, of those who do, many choose a career in consulting or with government offices, rather than embracing academia, once they have a PhD.\par \par \uc2 Prof Cornuel blames the declining social status of academics for this changing trend. Where once he says academics were well-respected and well-remunerated, this is no longer the case.\par \par \uc2 He predicts that the existing brain drain will speed up, with leading faculty moving to the US.\par \par \uc2 But it is the Bologna Declaration that promises to cause perhaps a seismic change in the European higher education landscape.\par \par \uc2 Continental Europe is to align its various higher education systems with the aim of providing greater transparency, rationalising degrees and increasing mobility.\par \par \uc2 The linchpin of Bologna is the switch from the five-year continental European masters-only system to the Anglo-Saxon Bachelors-Masters progression of four years plus a one-year masters or three years plus two-years masters.\par \par \uc2 Jeanette Purcell, chief executive officer of the London-based Association of MBAs, says the accord will have far-reaching implications for all business schools, not just those in continental Europe.\par \par \uc2 She predicts schools will have to alter their approach to marketing, selection of students and curriculum design. "It (Bologna) will force them to think about what they are offering and how to differentiate the MBA from a masters programme."\par \par \uc2 UK business schools, she says, for the most part have not recognised they will have to be more competitive, raise their profile and may have to redesign the programmes they are offering.\par \par \uc2 Programme redesign is one area with which European business schools are already very familiar.\par \par \uc2 Ms Purcell believes European schools are beginning to stand out in certain areas of the programmes that they offer.\par \par \uc2 Many schools are concentrating on developing leadership skills and personal effectiveness skills and paying far more attention to \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  and ethical issues, she says. These topics are taken far more seriously within Europe.\par \par \uc2 Another oft-cited area of excellence for European schools is that of the so-called soft skills.\par \par \uc2 Prof Cornuel believes that whereas 20 years ago European schools looked more towards the US model with a "more instrumental approach," the onus in Europe is now on the softer side.\par \par \uc2 "It is deeply embedded in Europe to take into consideration the human side of business."\par \par \uc2 But he adds, schools must alter the way in which they deliver these softer skills, making them more transversal and as applicable for example to marketing as they are to strategy. In other words, he says, "we must train the trainers".\par \par \uc2 However, one area perhaps where European business education lags behind its transatlantic cousins is that of entrepreneurship. While many US schools make entrepreneurship part of the core MBA, in Europe schools prefer to offer entrepreneurship as an elective subject.\par \par \uc2 Bert Twaalfhoven, entrepreneur and founder of the European Foundation for Entrepreneurship Research, is doing what he can to address this shortfall.\par \par \uc2 He plans to build a network of academics dedicated to addressing the entrepreneurial issues. "Teaching the teachers about entrepreneurship." European business schools, he says, do not appreciate how to teach entrepreneurship outside their own countries: how would a Spanish business expand into the Netherlands, for example. But with very few European case studies available, he admits it will be an uphill task.\par \par \uc2 Overall, business schools and management education in Europe receive a thumbs up from Prof Cornuel.\par \par \uc2 "I think there has been an incredible increase in quality in management education," he says. While EFMD is aware that some schools seek the Equis accreditation from EFMD purely to acquire a label, nevertheless, Prof Cornuel says the knock-on effect is beneficial, since these schools have to raise and maintain their standards to gain the accreditation.\par \par \uc2 In general, UK and continental European schools have limited resources compared with their US counterparts but Prof Cornuel says: "If you compare the budgets, what is done in the US compared with European institutions with the same budget, then I think they (European schools) are doing an excellent job with limited resources."\par \par \uc2 Although both European and US business schools have the same goal to teach an MBA, the gulf between the two remains.\par \par \uc2 Most obvious is the time factor, a two-year commitment in the US compared with 18, 16, 12 and even 10 months for a full-time MBA in Europe.\par \par \uc2 While the two-year model allows time for reflection, internships and job searches, this must be balanced against the opportunity and financial costs students incur. Increasingly it seems to be a price that participants are unwilling to pay.\par \par \uc2 US schools are aware of the issues. Richard Schmalensee, dean of the Sloan school at MIT, has voiced his concern about the two-year format and questions whether it will be dominant in the next 10 years.\par \par \uc2 Some US schools do offer the one-year format, for example Goizueta Business School at Emory and the Kellogg School at Northwestern University, but in general Ms Purcell says: "US schools are very reluctant to change their model and are digging their heels in."\par \par \uc2 She believes that the industry is moving away from the US model. "It has been demonstrated that an MBA can be done in a year. I don't see how you can sustain a two-year model."\par \par \uc2 Has the death-knell sounded for two-year programmes? Possibly, but certainly not in the short term; business education is a vast industry and there is room to accommodate a wide variety of models. But the popularity of part-time, distance and executive programmes is certainly on the rise.\par \par \uc2 Moreover, the Bologna Declaration means universities are designing a range of masters programmes that may well encroach on the traditional MBA field. European institutions face a challenging and exciting period. There may well be turbulent times ahead, but they certainly will not be dull.\par \par \uc2 The business education industry is undergoing a sea change. Difficult times have taken their toll and resulted in falling numbers of applicants who pay the high fees for the qualification that is seen as a ticket to the top jobs in international business. This has combined with an overhaul of the European higher education system to leave schools operating in a different \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  that seems to be favouring European institutions rather than their often-prestigious US rivals.\par \par \uc2 The key issues:\par \par \uc2 *RANKINGS: European schools appear to be outpacing their US competitors.\par \par \uc2 *THE BOLOGNA DECLARATION: Kai Peters of Ashridge explains the significance of this seminal move.\par \par \uc2 *US VISA RESTRICTIONS: Immigration restrictions and the possible introduction of costly security measures are deterring applicants from approaching US schools, while some potential candidates may prefer an education with a more international perspective.\par \par \uc2 *THE MBA EXPERIENCE: Two MBA graduates write about their time during and after business school. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 20040906S201.067\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intb