ED\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Surveys MUS1\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b PG\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 Page 5\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LA\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (c) 2004 The Financial Times Limited. All rights reserved \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The close identification of Bill Gates with Microsoft, the market-leading software company that he founded, has paid sizeable dividends in the form of a very favourable perception of the company as a responsible corporate citizen.\par \par \uc2 When chief executives and non-governmental organisations were asked which of the world's companies performed best on \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 , their answers propelled Microsoft to the top of the list. And a large proportion of those replies mentioned Bill Gates by name, citing his personal donations to charitable and health projects.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Technically, the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation is an entity separate from Microsoft the corporation, but that distinction seems to have been outweighed by the personal success of its chairman. Mr Gates's high-profile, and high-value, backing for projects tackling such important concerns as Aids and malaria in Africa have made a big impression, and his company is seen as mirroring the values his charitable donations represent. Microsoft is seen, both by chief executives and non-governmental organisations (NGOs), as helping in the education of disadvantaged children, looking after its own employees, and encouraging a wider awareness of corporate responsibility.\par \par \uc2 One of Microsoft's rivals, IBM, ranks second in the world for \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 , according to NGOs. Its main strengths appear to be its emphasis on environmental sustainability and its treatment of its employees.\par \par \uc2 In the case of organisations such as the International Committee of the Red Cross, Medecins sans Frontieres or Greenpeace, it is easy to see why NGOs rated them highly on \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 But some of the other names on the list might seem surprising.\par \par \uc2 BP, for instance, and Royal Dutch/Shell are two of the world's biggest oil producers. But their presence in the rankings - they took third and 15th place respectively - reflects a realisation some years ago on the part of both organisations that they would need to improve their reputations as polluters of the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Legislation has also had an important effect. As the Kyoto protocol on climate change comes into effect, the companies will have to reduce their carbon dioxide emissions. Both have already moved to do so - for instance, Lord Browne of BP was able to boast in 2002 that the company had met its pledge to cut its emissions by 10 per cent from 1990 levels by 2010 eight years early, and at no net cost to the company because doing so helped it to use less energy. NGOs have rewarded such policies in their votes for the oil companies in this year's rankings.\par \par \uc2 Just as surprising is the ranking of McDonald's at sixth place. The fast-food giant has been blamed for contributing to the epidemic of obesity that is sweeping the US and spreading to other developed countries. But it gained points among NGOs for its recent change of menus to include healthier options such as salads - "they are now becoming health conscious", as one respondent put it.\par \par \uc2 Body Shop has managed to preserve its place in the hearts of NGOs, rising one place from fifth last year to fourth in 2004. When it originally committed to eschew animal testing of its products, Body Shop was in a small minority of cosmetics companies, but today that policy is more widespread - something for which the retailer takes a slice of the credit.\par \par \uc2 Since then, Body Shop has also gained a reputation for assisting rather than exploiting its suppliers in the developing world - a policy also now being taken up more widely.\par \par \uc2 An entrant to the list is the UK's Co-operative Bank. The bank introduced an ethical policy in 1992 in line with its long history as part of the co-operative movement beginning in 1844 and it markets its commitment to responsible behaviour as a unique selling point, setting it apart from other financial institutions.\par \par \uc2 For instance, it will not invest in any government or business that fails to uphold human rights, or any business whose links to a repressive regime are a cause for concern. Its customers also have a say in setting its ethical policies.\par \par \uc2 Two companies fell out of the rankings from last year: Campbell Soup Company and DaimlerChrysler, with the latter case reflecting concern over the effect of motor transport on the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , and an increasingly fraught relationship between German car manufacturers and their employees.\par \par \uc2 Ikea, the Swedish furniture retailer, also took an unexpected tumble down the list, falling from third last year to 12th in this year's survey, in spite of retaining its commitment to \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies.\par \par \uc2 NGOs generally applauded companies that performed well financially as well as minimising their adverse environmental impact, and having a positive impact on the community at large.\par \par \uc2 Economic success was seen as an important complement to a sound ethical policy, as a way of disproving the common perception among business leaders that \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  is either irrelevant or can damage profits.\par \par \uc2 Typical comments from NGOs on companies they approved of included: "I respect companies that do well financially while simultaneously acting in a responsible manner" (said about IBM), and "very socially focused and still able to make money" (said about Virgin).\par \par \uc2 If companies such as Microsoft, BP and Coca-Cola can boast a healthy financial performance alongside a commitment to socially responsible behaviour, that may encourage their sceptical rivals to improve their practices. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 20041119S505.088\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 mcrost : \uc2 Microsoft Corporation\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\