 \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Klaus Kleinfeld Incoming chief executive Siemens\par \par \uc2 Tough-Minded Management by Joe Batten This business book influenced my leadership style strongly quite some time ago and made a lasting impression. The essentials are as valid today (maybe even more) as when the book was published in 1965.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 It captures all crucial leadership elements and - most importantly - focuses on strong and excellent employees as being the key to success in every company. It's about teamwork among excellent individuals working together for excellence - excellence which accepts no mediocrity. The book led me to two of my most important lessons in life: "Nobody is perfect, but a team can be" and "Work hard - play hard".\par \par \uc2 AG Lafley Chief executive, Procter &Gamble\par \par \uc2 Alexander Hamilton by Ron Chernow In early 2004, after surgery for my Achilles tendon, I read biographies of George Washington, John Adams and Thomas Jefferson to gain a deeper appreciation of the founding of the American Republic. Now I am reading about Alexander Hamilton, arguably the most American and certainly the most controversial founding father. An illegitimate orphan and self-taught immigrant, he was ambitious, individualistic and intent upon making an impact on the economy and politics of his time. The young Hamilton served as George Washington's aide-de-camp, as a member of the Constitutional Convention and principal writer of the Federalist Papers advocating adoption.\par \par \uc2 Most important, he was the first Treasury secretary of the US. He forged its budget and tax system, created the central bank, coast guard and customs service, and simply but powerfully laid the foundation for the American democracy and economy that still operate today. His character flaws and unbridled passion only make him more human and somehow more modern.\par \par \uc2 For 21st-century business leaders, Hamilton is arguably the most real, the most relevant and the most important founding father of the American Republic.\par \par \uc2 Tom Glocer chief executive, Reuters\par \par \uc2 The Wisdom of Crowds by James Surowiecki This was the only business book I read this year. I usually ask a group of people I trust which book they really rate, and then go for that. That way I avoid all the "me-too" books, or the ones about "how I turned the company around".\par \par \uc2 Surowiecki is a very good writer. I've read a lot of his New Yorker pieces, and he is usually engaging and succinct. If someone can write well you are halfway there. And this is a book of ideas. With most business books, if you read the first two chapters you've got the theory of it - the rest is case studies. Here there is more than just "do it this way and be a great manager". It's a level up from that. He is looking at some universal truths. It helps you in business, and beyond.\par \par \uc2 He cites the example of the Challenger (space shuttle) disaster. Here the market worked out what it took a committee months to conclude - that one company, Morton Thiokol, which made the booster rockets with the faulty O-ring seals, had been responsible for the explosion. It's a pretty powerful example.\par \par \uc2 The best business books influence you almost subconsciously so that their ideas just become part of what you think. It's not like reading one great man's life story. The important thoughts stay with you. You don't necessarily apply them directly, but you may see patterns and have more understanding as a result.\par \par \uc2 William McDonough Chairman of the US Public Company Accounting Oversight Board\par \par \uc2 Pay Without Performance: the Unfulfilled Promise of Executive Compensation by Lucian Bebchuk and Jesse Fried This book scares the hell out of you because it gives you the best insight into how super-CEOs exploited the system of executive compensation in the US.\par \par \uc2 Guy Dolle Chief executive, Arcelor\par \par \uc2 Competing Against Time: How Time-Based Competition is Reshaping Global Markets by George Stalk and Thomas Hout Time-based competition is the key concept of this book. Speed is as vital to compete and succeed in the steel industry as it is, for example, in information technology. This applies as much to strategy execution and project management as to supply-chain performance. In our industry, efficient time management is vital for customer service and inventory optimisation. It is a competitive differentiator and a key indicator for operational excellence.\par \par \uc2 Time is quantifiable and manageable if you focus properly on it. The book was written in 1990, before the digital revolution that reshaped many business activities. Interestingly, this evolution, rather than obliterating the concepts developed by Stalk and Hout, has added to their pertinence and importance. The competitive advantages of fast and good timing have been massively leveraged over the past decade.\par \par \uc2 Rod Eddington Chief executive, British Airways\par \par \uc2 Winning! by Sir Clive Woodward Sir Clive's book captures some really interesting ideas on successful teams and what is needed to win without compromising any important values. And it uses sport as a vehicle to understand organisations and what makes them successful.\par \par \uc2 Leif O stling Chief executive, Scania\par \par \uc2 Up the Organization by Robert Townsend This might not be the most well-known management literature and it is definitely not the thickest book in this field, but I liked it. It focuses on what is important in management, and is healthily free of high-sounding empty phrases since it is written by a person who has experienced what he is talking about.\par \par \uc2 Mr Townsend was chief executive of Avis Rent-a-Car in the 1960s and the man behind the successful redirection of the company. "We try harder" (the Avis slogan) is a good guiding star for a company that wants to be the number one in the market.\par \par \uc2 Stephen Crawford Chief administrative officer, Morgan Stanley\par \par \uc2 The Wisdom of Crowds by James Surowiecki This book implicitly validates the idea that the very big crowd we call "the market" - with all its imperfections and shortcomings - is still a better allocator of resources than any of the alternatives. It also makes a compelling case for why, in the long run, a genuinely diverse organisation will tend to make better decisions than a homogeneous one.\par \par \uc2 Patrick Harker Dean, Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania\par \par \uc2 The Fortune at the Bottom of the Pyramid: Eradicating Poverty through Profits by C.K. Prahalad Prahalad challenges businesses, governments and academia to stop looking at the poor in the world as victims but rather as potential employees and customers, in this new book published by Wharton. In so doing, he is offering a very different approach for helping expand economies and provide hope in the developing world.\par \par \uc2 Martin Sorrell Chief executive, WPP\par \par \uc2 The Economic Theory of Managerial Capitalism by Robin Marris Although a theoretical book by a Cambridge economist, I remember this book having the greatest impact on me during three years of my economics degree. It stimulated my interest in business and marked out the differences between economic theory and practical capitalism. It had a remarkable impact on my thinking.\par \par \uc2 Ian Davis Managing director, McKinsey &Company\par \par \uc2 The Blank Slate by Steven Pinker I find it difficult to get beyond the introduction of most business books. Not so with this one, perhaps because it is not primarily a business book.\par \par \uc2 Pinker's analysis of human nature and intellectual life made me think differently about how people and organisational cultures develop. It is provocative and it is a very good read.\par \par \uc2 Sarah Hogg Chairwoman, 3i Group\par \par \uc2 Journey to Lean, by John Drew, Blair McCallum and Stefan Roggenhofer; Enterprise,by Roger Parry; and Simply Better, by Patrick Barwise and Sean Meehan. These are three very different books: Journey to Leanis an excellent nuts-and-bolts book on operations; Enterprise brings the personal experience of a great corporate leader; and Simply Better is an excellent blend of academic expertise on marketing with commonsense focus on the customer.\par \par \uc2 Daniel Vasella Chairman and chief executive, Novartis\par \par \uc2 Back to the Drawing Board by Colin Carter and Jay Lorsch This book is an excellent aid for thinking through concrete matters as they relate to the composition and structure of the board as well as key processes, for example the exchange of information, review of strategy or succession planning. There are insights and advice one can relate to as a board member such as how to build trust, shorten presentations and stimulate more in-depth dialogue. It is an invaluable source for better governance practice.\par \par \uc2 Steve Riggio Chief executive, Barnes &Noble\par \par \uc2 The March of Folly by Barbara Tuchman I am not a big reader of business books, so I have an atypical candidate. I read it when it was published (in 1984) but find its lessons timeless, so I go back to it often. Tuchman explores four events in history (Trojan war, Renaissance popes who provoked the Protestant Reformation, the British losing America and the US in Vietnam) to demonstrate how governments pursued policies contrary to their own interest.\par \par \uc2 The analogy works for me in the business world as it is tempting for companies to engage in reckless actions against their competitors in hopes of building market share when all along they should be investing in ways to create stronger ties to their core customers. If you stare at your competitors too long, you eventually lose sight of your customer.\par \par \uc2 Tony Juniper Director, Friends of the Earth\par \par \uc2 The Corporation: the Pathological Pursuit of Profit and Power by Joel Bakan This book provides us all with a timely reminder that we are responsible not only for the way in which corporations behave but also, more importantly, for determining the framework they operate within.\par \par \uc2 Bakan persuasively puts the case that the modern corporation has gained its power through changes to the law and follows through the argument to show how changes to the law could ensure that corporations more effectively meet our common needs. Profit is a powerful motive for modern business, but what good is profit if it destroys the natural resources we all rely upon?\par \par \uc2 I'd like to see company executives and \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  advisers read this book before they make their annual reports on the company's progress. Just in case any of them have forgotten that protecting society and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  does, in fact, make good business sense.\par \par \uc2 Wim Roelandts Chief executive, Xilinx\par \par \uc2 The Rise and Fall of Strategic Planning by Henry Mintzberg This gives an excellent history of the strategic planning process over the past 40 years. It is very interesting in a sense that none of these processes really worked. Mintzberg does an outstanding job in analysing the reasons why these systems failed, which in itself contains a tremendous amount of learning about what does not work, the misconceptions people had (we are talking about large, significant companies) and the difficulties of implementing their processes.\par \par \uc2 Then Mintzberg proposes a plan of his own, based on separating strategy from the planning of the execution of that strategy. This is a much better approach to the problem of strategic planning than any other I have seen and, in my own expertise, has a much better chance of success and corresponds better with the realities of strategy and planning in today's enterprise.\par \par \uc2 Jonathan Schwartz President and chief operating officer, Sun Microsystems\par \par \uc2 Empires of Light by Jill Jonnes; Wine and War: the French, the Nazis, and the Battle for France's Greatest Treasure, by Donald and Petie Kladstrup The computing industry is entering a phase where the greatest challenges to reaching new opportunities are not technical but cultural. In many ways, this mirrors the transitions other industries such as electricity and telecommunications have undergone. Empires of Light, on the history of the electrical industry, elucidates the battles of the nascent electricity market and infuses them with the real personalities of the people involved. A book not to be missed if you want to understand how maturing industries move from worlds of complete customisation to standardisation to utilisation, and spawn profound new opportunities - indeed sometimes whole new industries and innovations.\par \par \uc2 I love the exploration involved in sampling new wines, so I enjoyed Wine and War. Lovers of wine around the world will certainly appreciate the clever and ingenious methods with which folks protected their most sacred treasure from the hands of the German invaders - and the risks they were willing to take for their passion.\par \par \uc2 Greg Josefowicz Chief executive, Borders Group\par \par \uc2 Confronting Reality by Ram Charan and Larry Bossidy This is particularly relevant for such companies as Borders Group operating in the fast-moving retail space where change is constant and customers give you a report card each day. The authors challenge companies to assess with unflinching honesty the existing business model and they provide real insight into managing through change.\par \par \uc2 The book has added meaning at Borders because we have been fortunate to have Charan work with us in a consulting capacity. We have been challenged directly to think through and act on the insights in Confronting Reality.\par \par \uc2 Guler Sabanci Chairwoman, Sabanci Holding\par \par \uc2 The Road Less Traveled by M. Scott Peck At the beginning of my career, this book increased my awareness of the issues of psychological and spiritual development in business life. For anyone who is intent on pursuing an established career, the recommendations and the attitude of the book would be a good starting guide.\par \par \uc2 Andrew Butt Managing director, Enable Software\par \par \uc2 The E-Myth Revisited by Michael Gerber The author talks about working on the business as opposed to in the business, and explains how many entrepreneurs are actually technicians - very good at the technical details of the ideas they are passionate about and later the businesses they create, but not always very good at running a business.\par \par \uc2 He looks at systematising the different processes within the business by writing scripts, and then employing people with the right (positive) attitude but not necessarily experience to follow those scripts and run the business.\par \par \uc2 Gerber also looks at how "stepping back" from the detail allows the entrepreneur to focus on the big picture and steer the business to great success.\par \par \uc2 Richard Reed Co-founder, Innocent Drinks\par \par \uc2 Eating the Big Fish, by Adam Morgan; Good to Great, by Jim Collins I haven't read a business book that left a lasting impression on me this year but the ones that have most left an impression since setting up the business are Eating the Big Fish and Good to Great. Meanwhile, the film The Corporation - also a book - has sharpened my sense that we have got to make some adjustments to the capitalist system to stop us all killing ourselves - if you haven't seen the film I strongly recommend it. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 20041223L114.074\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 prgml : \uc2 The Procter & Gamble Company\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 i25 : \uc2 Chemicals | i258 : \uc2 Cosmetics/Toiletries | icnp : \uc2 Consumer Products | ipcare : \uc2 Personal Care Products/Appliances\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \