ocial responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 ."\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 There is a lot of this hoo-ha here. Professor Klaus Schwab, the sonorous Swiss founder of the forum, is forever confusing the roles of business and government. He exhorts executives to be good corporate citizens, curb HIV-AIDS, battle mosquitoes in Tanzania and promote "equitable globalization." It took a politician -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair -- to remind participants that the first responsibility of business is to "make a profit."\par \par \uc2 Nursing my theory, I went in search of Hewlett-Packard CEO Carly Fiorina, who, given the disquiet on her board reported by this newspaper last week, was arguably the last CEO who ought to have been here. She was scheduled to speak at a session -- and I'm not making this up -- titled "Does Business Have a Noble Purpose?" But she canceled.\par \par \uc2 Later, I caught up with Ms. Fiorina at a small coffee for reporters. I first asked her to describe her relations with her board of directors, and she snapped: "Excellent." Next question.\par \par \uc2 When I asked what value her shareholders get from her trip to Davos, she replied: "I get the opportunity to meet with a huge number of customers," citing a breakfast that day with Mr. Blair. This was less than convincing, because I doubt Mr. Blair gets involved in his government's IT purchasing decisions.\par \par \uc2 THEN SHE MOVED to point two (Ms. Fiorina answers many questions with a numbered list). "Every one of the issues talked about here impacts my company. The day when business and government were totally separate spheres is over. Public policy and business practice are inextricably linked."\par \par \uc2 She isn't alone in this view. Even Pfizer's Hank McKinnell, known in his industry for a humorless focus on shareholder value, says he decided several years ago that he had to take a broader view of his job. Outside the U.S., AIDS activists had painted the pharmaceuticals industry "as part of the problem." And inside the U.S., the industry had come under attack for charging high prices and blocking cheaper imports from overseas. In that \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the old approach -- which he described as "paying attention to our business . . . and hoping for the best" -- no longer sufficed.\par \par \uc2 SO MR. MCKINNELL has become an iconic business statesman, serving as vice chairman of the World Economic Forum's board, chairman of the Business Roundtable and a political activist. In Davos, he sponsored a reception in honor of U.S. Sen. Bill Frist, the Republican majority leader, who he expects will make health care the centerpiece of his 2008 presidential campaign.\par \par \uc2 The pharmaceuticals industry may be a special case, peculiarly exposed to the whims of public policy. But it is surprising how many such "special cases" now exist. Certainly the telecommunications industry, the financial-services industry, the health-care industry, and all businesses that depend on trade or intellectual property find their survival dependent in part on government actions. One of the ironies of today's business world is that, despite the movement toward reliance on market forces in the past three decades, CEOs find it necessary to pay more attention to government than ever. If you doubt that, just track the corporate jets flying into Washington and Brussels.\par \par \uc2 That is the motivating idea behind this new column, which will run every Wednesday. I hope to view the world of business, perhaps not from the thin-aired altitude of the Swiss Alps, but at least from the elevation of the executive suite, where business and economics and public policy have become increasingly intertwined.\par \par \uc2 I still have my doubts about whether Ms. Fiorina should have been in Davos. But she spoke a truth about today's business.\par \par \uc2 ---\par \par \uc2 What responsibilities do CEOs have when it comes to addressing social issues? Join Alan Murray and give your views at WSJ.com/Discussions. \par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.djreprints.com/link/DJRFactiva.html?FACTIVA=wjco20050202000059"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 License this article from Dow Jones Reprint Service}}}\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 gglblz : \uc2 Globalization | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | gcat : \uc2 Political/General News | gcom : \uc2 Society/Community/Work | gglobe : \uc2 Global/World Issues | ncat : \uc2 Content Types | nfact : \uc2 Factiva Filters | ccsr : \uc2 Corporate Social Responsibility | nfcpex : \uc2 FC&E Executive News Filter\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RE\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faaut