in the UK will change how companies disclose their environmental record. And as climate change becomes a mainstream concern, investors will demand more information\par \par \uc2 This year, UK companies will come under more pressure than ever to spell out how they are responding to environmental issues, such as climate change. From March, companies will be required to file alongside their annual reports an operating and financial review (OFR), in which directors will have to make forward-looking statements about the "key drivers" of a business.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Although it will not be obligatory to include environmental factors in that discussion, they feature prominently in the OFR guidance supplied by the Department for Trade and Industry, which says board members will have to acknowledge if such issues have been excluded. In practice, the OFR will require greater disclosure on the extent to which environmental issues underpin a company's performance or trends likely to affect it in the future. For example, rises of up to 30 per cent in the cost of fuel, such as gas and electricity, are sure to affect directly the bottom line. Although pressure groups accuse the government of a "greenwash" by not making disclosure of environmental policies mandatory, many companies will find that the proposed levels of environmental reporting go beyond the \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  and sustainability reports that they currently issue. The extent to which they exceed current requirements depends on the company's proximity to the problems of energy efficiency and climate change.\par \par \uc2 For the most energy-intensive industries, such as utilities, chemical producers, and glass and steel manufacturers, the introduction in January of the EU emissions trading system (EU ETS) means that their carbon emissions already will have a quantifiable value. Other sectors, including aviation, are likely to be included in the next phase of ETS starting in 2008. They are expected to estimate the impact of participation in the scheme as part of their forward-looking OFRs. Because of the growing cost of energy usage, such companies are also likely to face shareholder pressure to reveal more about planned measures to improve energy efficiency. Some companies already do this, especially when they can reveal big savings.\par \par \uc2 BP says that in its first three years of actively pursuing improved energy efficiency and emissions reduction, it generated Pounds 650m from an investment of Pounds 20m. In a less energy-intensive sector, Boots, the high street chemists, has an energy bill of Pounds 20m on sales of Pounds 5.3bn. Nonetheless, it reports saving Pounds 1m-2m from reducing carbon emissions by 10,000 tonnes.\par \par \uc2 Although such figures may look impressive, it is difficult to compare the environmental records of different companies, even within the same sector. The OFR does not spell out which key performance indicators companies should use to disclose their environmental performance and, to date, there are no standard metrics. Defra, the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  ministry, provides guidance on various greenhouse gases that should be measured, such as carbon dioxide and methane, as well as the company's record on waste and water. But it leaves open the question of whether carbon emissions should be measured per employee, per unit of output or per pound of turnover. "Despite the impression of general improvement in (environmental) disclosure, it's not very easy to take apart and compare," says Nick Robins, head of sustainable and responsible investments at Henderson Global Investors. "You could have the top 50 companies in the UK using slightly different methodologies."\par \par \uc2 There is also disagreement about whether companies that are not gas guzzlers, such as technology or media companies, should include environmental matters within an OFR. Mr Robins says many such companies will be able to continue using their \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  report to explain their environmental record. Craig Mackenzie, head of Insight Investment, the asset management branch of HBOS, says there are many industrial sectors in which climate change will not be a significant factor for the next 10 years or so. For them, there is little point clogging up the OFR with environmental issues, especially if any measures taken have little impact on the company's value. But it is only if there is resounding evidence in the coming years that the window for dealing with climate change is closing that mainstream shareholders - as opposed to "ethical investors" - will begin to clamour for more disclosure. "Suddenly, all manner of sectors would find it a strategic issue," says Mr Mackenzie.\par \par \uc2 The climate change issue reaches the boardroom\par \par \uc2 Business has traditionally treated the reduction of carbon emissions and the development of energy policies as a technical issue and, therefore, the responsibility of operational managers. But as concern about the threat posed by climate change increases, it is increasingly common for the chairman of the board and chief executive to get involved. This has been the case at BP, the oil and gas giant, whose experience illustrates some of the environmental issues likely to come before directors as climate change moves higher up the corporate agenda. For BP, it is perhaps not surprising that the issue is dealt with at the highest level. The company's main product is at the heart of the problem, because the burning of fossil fuels, such as petrol, is one of the main causes of greenhouse gases. At BP, Lord Browne, chief executive, devises the company's environmental strategy and has pioneered the effort to transform its image into a greener "energy company".\par \par \uc2 According to David Pearl, BP's deputy company secretary who monitors the company's ethics and \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  assurance committee (EEAC), there has been a board-level group devoted to health, safety and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  at BP since the early 1990s. Broadly speaking, the committee's remit relates to non-financial risks and the potential damage to the company's reputation. Just as an audit committee would make sure there are no Enron-style surprises lurking in the company's finances, so the EEAC guards against potential environmental hazards that could do long-term damage to BP's image. This includes tracking issues ranging from headline grabbing ones, such as oil spills, to local but insidious problems, such as leakage from tanks on the forecourts of petrol stations. The committee reviews what environmental information goes into the company's annual report, the sustainability report and on to BP's website, and has a checklist for monitoring issues, such as greenhouse gas emissions. "For a natural resources company like BP, you have a huge potential liability if you're not managing it," Mr Pearl explains.\par \par \uc2 The EEAC is staffed by four non-executives who meet about five times a year. It invites both internal and external auditors to every meeting and strives to be quantitative. Therefore, it measures BP's environmental record against a set of internal targets set by the company. Not all companies will warrant the attention BP gives to the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Indeed, some of its competitors, such as ExxonMobil, are far more sceptical about global warming altogether. For those that do not need a separate committee, there are other ways boards can deal with risk: either through the audit committee, or a general risk committee that assesses non-financial concerns. As the workload of audit committees increases and environmental concerns rise, the latter is likely to be more common.\par \par \uc2 Even at those companies where climate change is not a pressing issue, boards can still keep an eye on the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Richard Sheath, director of Independent Audit, a company that specialises in corporate governance, says the challenge for board members is to identify the risks and ensure controls are applied. Environmental risks need to be assessed at the macro level, before controls are put in place, and at the micro level, after controls are factored in, he says. Mr Sheath breaks down risk into three main areas: strategic; financial and operational. Strategic risks might include such forward-looking events as global warming. Financial risks are those from regulatory costs. At the operational level, it might be pollution, regulation or the reputation damage caused by not doing anything about the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Of course, these risks are not confined to energy-intensive industries. Banks, for example, need to factor in the environmental risks when they make a loan to a large construction project, for fear they might become liable if the project backfires. Irrespective of the industry or sector, tackling the question sooner, rather than later, makes sense. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cel