ght\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LA\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (c) 2005 Dow Jones & Company, Inc. To see the edition in which this article appeared, click here    \uc2 http://awsj.com.hk/factiva-ns\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 MANY TOP EXECUTIVES are besieged these days by nonprofit groups seeking help for a myriad of causes. They realize that corporate efforts to improve society can enhance their company's reputation, but it isn't always easy to know which projects to support.    \par \par \uc2 The old model of corporate philanthropy no longer works. Steel magnate Andrew Carnegie, for example, donated millions of dollars of his fortune to build libraries, universities and museums. But he also badly polluted towns where his steel mills operated and dealt harshly with workers, even hiring Pinkerton guards to shoot at strikers.    \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Nowadays, civic largess won't make up for shoddy treatment of employees, customers or the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Beyond decent management practices, though, \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  presents a dizzying array of choices, from programs to recycle office stationery to funding for schools in Africa to research on global warming.    \par \par \uc2 The solution for an increasing number of chief executive officers is to focus on programs that directly relate to and benefit their businesses. "It's very difficult for a CEO to rationalize why you're spending a certain percentage of your top line on philanthropy," says Orin Smith, president and CEO of Starbucks. His company has been making charitable contributions since it was launched in 1971, he says, "but now we also build social responsibility into our business model."    \par \par \uc2 TO MOTIVATE HOURLY employees and build a stronger connection with them -- which can pay off in improved customer service -- Starbucks pays its workers more than the minimum wage and offers health benefits to any who work at least 20 hours a week. In addition, for every hour an employee devotes to a charity or community project, the company donates $10. Employees who have volunteered for this "make your mark" program have cleaned beaches in California and worked at day-care centers and hospices. "One way to inspire employees is to create a company they feel proud to be part of," Mr. Smith says.    \par \par \uc2 A few years ago, when activists in the "fair trade" movement -- which advocates fair payments to farmers in developing nations -- accused Starbucks of underpaying coffee growers, the company opened its books to them to prove that wasn't the case, Mr. Smith says. But since then, Starbucks has started buying more fair-trade coffee. This year it expects to spend about $10 million on fair-trade beans, up from $2.1 million in 2003. It also is negotiating long-term contracts with coffee growers who farm in environmentally friendly ways and is helping to fund schools and health-care clinics for their workers.    \par \par \uc2 "Only a small proportion of customers buys a company's products because it is socially responsible," Mr. Smith says. "But if they think for a moment that you aren't responsible, a much larger percentage will have a negative response" and potentially stop buying from you.    \par \par \uc2 Nonetheless, \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate\b0 \highlight\uc2 -\b \highlight22\uc2 social\b0 \highlight\uc2 -\b \highlight22\uc2 responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  initiatives also serve as forms of advertising and brand building, says Shelly Lazarus, CEO of WPP Group's Ogilvy & Mather. She believes that "customers get impressions about products from hundreds of sources, but when they believe a company is a good citizen, they feel more positively about a brand."    \par \par \uc2 HER AD AGENCY recently developed a campaign for Unilever's Dove soap with this idea in mind. It uses the slogan "campaign for real beauty" and shows women who are wrinkled, chubby or freckled, announcing, "We believe beauty comes in many shapes, sizes and ages." To supplement its ads, Unilever has donated money to a "self-esteem fund" to support educational programs for girls that may help counter eating disorders and other problems.    \par \par \uc2 Unilever doesn't advertise all its philanthropy, though. After the tsunami disaster, the company's employees in Sri Lanka used Unilever trucks to distribute medicine, food and other supplies. "Our people straight away used the skills they had without any cues from top management," Unilever Chairman Anthony Burgmans says. "This is what it means to be human," he says, but he agrees that such spontaneous charity also reflects well on the company.    \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  also can lead to new business opportunities. Citigroup has funded some microfinance initiatives in developing countries for decades. Last year it decided to look at some of them as a business opportunity, appointing a banker to develop services and products for microlending programs, initially in Mexico and India. The company doesn't expect to make a profit from these projects anytime soon, but it does hope to learn more about expanding in developing regions.    \par \par \uc2 Many corporations have learned a lot about image making since the days of the robber barons. "Companies that make unhealthy products, such as cigarettes, aren't going to be able to offset that with philanthropy," says Timothy Smith, senior vice president and director of socially responsible investing at Walden Asset Management. "But those who say being socially responsible just costs money and detracts from the bottom line are wrong. It can boost the bottom line and add value for investors."    \par \par \uc2 ---    \par \par \uc2 E-mail comments to inthelead@wsj.com. To see other recent columns, go to CareerJournal.com.    \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\c