te on \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 ,insightfully highlighted in your recent report and editorial on how Chinese suppliers try to cover up irregularities such as excessive working hours, underpayment and sub-standard health and safety arrangements, raises some concern in a country like Sweden.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 My country is small and highly dependent on open markets and free trade. This has made Sweden an international country. The main road to economic growth and prosperity in times of globalisation goes through free and open trade combined with a strong engagement for CSR. We see a clear link between responsible business behaviour and the acceptance of a just and fair globalisation that benefits all. CSR is not about protectionism, but about establishing a floor for human decency in business. By aligning business practices with universal norms and principles, such as UN Global Compact and the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development Guidelines for Multinational Enterprises, we can create responsible growth.\par \par \uc2 The Swedish government believes that intense work on CSR is a prerequisite for the acceptance of continued globalisation. But it is also a way to make free and fair trade the vehicle for economic growth that our world economy needs. Many companies have recognised a clear business case for responsible behaviour. To them, responsible business codes and practices are not a short-term cost, but a long-term investment. More and more governments realise that sustainable development requires the business community to get engaged - not only as an employer in the traditional sense, but also as one that contributes to the advancement of decent working conditions, human rights, the fight against corruption and a sound and healthy \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Sweden is chairing this week's OECD ministerial meeting "Enabling Globalisation". In conjunction with the ministerial, an open forum will take place. I have arranged for one of the forum panels to focus on CSR to demonstrate the importance of this issue to the debate on the challenges and opportunities in globalisation. My messages to the panel will be clear: CSR must not be turned into another protectionist instrument; we have to support countries that are CSR-conscious, but still have difficulties working with these issues, and we need to make sure that company commitment to CSR translates into practical outcomes on the ground.\par \par \uc2 I will ask fellow OECD governments to step up inter-governmental co-operation and dialogue. We need to be clear on how we can create an enabling \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  for responsible business practices. This will also contribute to the enhancement of the important role of business in meeting the Millennium Development Goals.\par \par \uc2 Thomas O stros, Minister of Industry and Trade, Sweden \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 20050503E114.024\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intb