\li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 When recruiting from the business world, international public sector organisations often attract executives from the business world who are prepared to accept a lower salary for a career they consider more rewarding.\par \par \uc2 These days, however, non-profit organisations no longer have the monopoly on improving life for poor communities or preserving the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 . "\b \highlight22\uc2 Corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 " and "sustainability" are increasingly embedded in companies' policies, so opportunities to work on projects fostering development are increasing in the private sector.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 "As more companies are getting into this area, we're a really good source of trained executives," says Dorothy Berry, vice-president of human resources and administration at the International Finance Corporation, the private finance arm of the World Bank.\par \par \uc2 "It really is a challenge for us, both on the recruitment and the training side, because we invest a lot in training staff and, just at the point where they're most productive, they leave us."\par \par \uc2 An additional obstacle to recruiting MBA graduates or keeping top executives is the upturn in business and the financial sector, says Ms Berry.\par \par \uc2 "In the past three years it was a boom for us, so when we'd go to recruit at business schools we'd have standing room only. Now the market is changing as the economy has picked up in different places and this is the first year we've had MBA graduates turn us down."\par \par \uc2 The IFC is responding by introducing a new programme through which it is targeting graduates not only of well-known business schools in the US and Europe but also from business education institutions in the developing world. At the same time, it is establishing internships with the schools and building relationships with students and professors.\par \par \uc2 At the senior management level, demographic changes are playing a role in the international public sector's increasingly urgent recruitment drive as a wave of retirements hits the sector. "There's a lot of leadership change going on in that sector and it seems that there's not always lot of succession planning," says Mike Kirkman, head of the education, non-profit and public policy practice at Spencer Stuart, the recruitment firm. "So they're going outside for new leaders."\par \par \uc2 But while non-profit and non-governmental organisations (NGOs) may face ever more intense competition when it comes to attracting business executives, recruiters and public sector organisations also report a growing interest on the part of corporate managers in entering the sector.\par \par \uc2 At Amnesty International UK, efforts to broaden the organisation's recruitment base by redesigning advertising campaigns and broadening advertised job specifications seem to be paying off. "We are seeing more private sector applications - in the past couple of years, just under half (of job applications) came from the private sector and that's a big increase," says June Hall, human resources director at Amnesty International UK.\par \par \uc2 Part of the reason is that career prospects in the international public sector are improving.\par \par \uc2 As organisations become more global - and increasingly professional in their approach - there are opportunities for employees to rise up through an organisation, and to travel widely or accept a foreign posting.\par \par \uc2 "If you're talented and young and want to get into a non-profit, there are plenty of available roles," says Mr Kirkman. "And if you're outstanding and you demonstrate that, it's a place where people can really thrive and move up the ladder within the field pretty swiftly."\par \par \uc2 While public sector employers cannot offer the bonuses and stock options used by the private sector to increase the appeal of their jobs, multilateral institutions, non-profit organisations and NGOs tend to place a strong emphasis on workplace diversity and often are able to offer flexible working hours, part-time jobs or school-term-time positions.\par \par \uc2 However, the strongest motivator for corporate executives who decide to leave well-paid positions in business for a job in the international public sector remains the desire to have their beliefs and ideals reflected in the work they do.\par \par \uc2 "The price tag is not as important as it used to be," says Susana Malcorra, deputy executive director of the World Food Programme. Ms Malcorra spent 25 years in the corporate sector in business management, finance and information technology before joining the WFP in July last year.\par \par \uc2 "I felt that I had done a lot in the corporate world and proved myself in the corporate world, and was ready to do something more meaningful," she says.\par \par \uc2 Mr Kirkman has seen many corporate managers express similar sentiments. "You've got a whole cadre of executives in their 50s in the latter part of their career. They've made money in corporate life and there seems to be an increasing desire to return that blessing," he says. At the same time, he adds, "you're seeing younger people thinking about making a career in this space".\par \par \uc2 Ms Malcorra believes the reason for this is that, for many people, the sort of work carried out by organisations such as the WFP can prove more satisfying than commercial activities. "We don't have a bottom line," she says. "But we have to get to the recipients quickly otherwise people will starve to death. So it's much more compelling than the quarterly closing with profits." \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 20050505S302.165\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | ncat : \uc2 Content Types | nfact : \uc2 Factiva Filters | nfcpin : \uc2 FC&E Industry News Filter | crecrt : \uc2 Recruitment | c42 : \uc2 Labor/Personnel Issues | ccsr : \uc2 Corporate Social Responsibility | nfcpex : \uc2 FC&E Executive News Filter\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\l