lers about Brussels but one is in the pipeline. Fiery Frits Bolkestein is to publish his memoirs this month.\par \par \uc2 The Dutch ex-internal market commissioner, dubbed Frankenstein by leftwingers who oppose his plan to increase competition in services, is rushing the book out just six months after stepping down. And it could be incendiary, Observer hears.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 "He kept a diary during his time in Brussels, writing something every day," says Observer's man with the manuscript. "It will contain some juicy bits."\par \par \uc2 Quite. "Balkanstein", who is now taking on the Turks, has never been shy of a fight. He has squared up to everyone from Gordon Brown, Britain's brooding prime minister-in-waiting, to hard-left French unions, who cut off the electricity supply to his home in France.\par \par \uc2 While commissioners such as Karel van Miert and Lord Jenkins have written memoirs, they waited several years. Some of those Balkanstein clashed with, such as German industry commissioner Gunter Verheugen, are still in office in Brussels. He does not need official permission.\par \par \uc2 The book will be published in Dutch on May 26, just before the June 1 referendum on the European constitution in the Netherlands. Though he is ostensibly backing the Yes campaign, Bolkestein's talk of Brussels' legislative diarrhoea will win it few votes.\par \par \uc2 Balkanstein himself is now in Vienna, writing a comparison of the European Union and the Austro-Hungarian empire, a ramshackle, multi-ethnic construction that lost the support of its people and collapsed in 1918.\par \par \uc2 Political goals\par \par \uc2 Not even Balkanstein can get the Dutch as excited as football can. So with the Yes campaign for the constitution struggling to fire up a sceptical electorate, treaty fans - including Mark Rutte, education secretary - turned to the national sport to inject life into the debate with a friendly match against No supporters.\par \par \uc2 The No team won - on penalties. In that respect the match did have something in common with the June 1 ballot, which looks like being every bit as close.\par \par \uc2 Total-ly deaf\par \par \uc2 How saddening for Total that its small shareholders do not share the concern for "open dialogue with our partners and with civil society" that the French oil giant recently boasted about in its \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  report.\par \par \uc2 When a human rights activist stood up at yesterday's annual meeting in Paris to ask if it was considering pulling out of a gas project in Burma, which provides critical support to the country's military junta, he was greeted with booing and jeering.\par \par \uc2 The cat-calls and abuse from the 7,000-strong audience were so loud that Thierry Desmarest, Total's chief executive, had to appeal for the man to be heard.\par \par \uc2 Not that Desmarest was sympathetic. Total would not withdraw from Burma, he replied, as "we believe in the link between economic development and respect for human rights".\par \par \uc2 His small shareholders do not agree. Despite seeing their stock rise almost 50 per cent in two years, they are not willing to let anything be said that could stain the reputation - and share price - of their beloved national champion.\par \par \uc2 Shipshape\par \par \uc2 With impeccable timing, the Union of Greek Shipowners will visit Brussels tomorrow, but clearly not with the aim of fuelling the controversy over Jose Manuel Barroso's yachting holiday last summer, courtesy of his Greek friend and shipping tycoon Spiros Latsis.\par \par \uc2 Indeed, Observer found the Greeks remarkably cagey about whether the Commission president would be among the commission officials whom they are set to meet.\par \par \uc2 The answer seems to be No and of course Latsis himself is not expected to indulge in a bit of Brussels hospitality. Perhaps Barroso has finally learned to obey the old maxim: "Beware of Greek-bearing ships."\par \par \uc2 Greek greens\par \par \uc2 A Greek \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  commissioner seems like an oxymoron: Greece is the only member of the EU without an \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  minister.\par \par \uc2 And while Stavros Dimas, ex-Wall Street banker, beavers away on matters green in Brussels, the stink over sewage back home grows ever stronger. The latest casualty is Sifis Glyniadakis, chairman and chief executive of the partly privatised Athens Water and Sewage Company (which is better at the latter than the former).\par \par \uc2 He has been forced to resign after upping his monthly salary by ?3,000 and hiring a bunch of consultants without asking his political bosses.\par \par \uc2 There has also been much questioning of why Glyniadakis and his highly paid team haven't managed to dent a growing mountain of sludge next to the Athens waste treatment plant on the uninhabited islet of Psyttaleia. Taverna owners in nearby Piraeus are complaining that tourists will be driven away by noxious odours hitting the waterfront.\par \par \uc2 Persuading a qualified manager to sign up for this dirty job will be hard for the governing New Democracy party, not least since it has axed 13 politically appointed bosses in the 14 months since it came to power.\par \par \uc2 Uzbek gold\par \par \uc2 Another company suffering from association with an autocratic regime is Oxus Gold, the London-listed mining company whose only producing asset is in Uzbekistan. Its shares fell 14 per cent on Monday after hundreds of protestors were killed in the central Asian country last week.\par \par \uc2 Chief executive Bill Trew told Dow Jones: "All our operations are continuing totally unaffected. In fact, we've just had a record week last week, so it's a bit irritating to see people marking our stock down so violently." At least it is only his shares that are being hit violently. observer@ft.com \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 42414512\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 eec : \uc2 European Union | ghum : \uc2 Human Rights/Civil Liberties | gcat : \uc2 Political/General News | gcom : \uc2 Society/Community/Work | ocat : \uc2 International Pol-Econ Organizations\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faa