i0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Handling more than 3m passenger journeys a day on the capital's tube system, employees of London Underground frequently find themselves in highly pressured situations.\par \par \uc2 Three years ago, LU highlighted the costs of stress-related absence and secured funding for a health plan to tackle it.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 LU, which receives a "big tick" in this year's Business in the Community (BITC) awards for excellence, introduced a stress reduction programme using cognitive behavioural therapy to help employees better understand and cope with stress.\par \par \uc2 Managers were also given a toolkit including guides on handling stress, advice cards on how to conduct back-to-work interviews with staff returning from sickness absence, "relaxation CDs" containing information and exercises, and a dedicated email address for requests for help with stress problems.\par \par \uc2 Sickness absence has fallen by considerably more than LU's initial target. According to figures submitted to BITC, this has generated annual savings of Pounds 455,000, equal to a return on investment of 8:1.\par \par \uc2 The stress programme is short-listed along with initiatives by six other organisations, including AstraZeneca, Ernst &Young and 3M, for the UnumProvident Healthy Workplaces Award. It is one of three new awards that, combined with many entries to established awards, underline how treatment of employees has become a vital strand of corporate responsibility.\par \par \uc2 "To be a responsible business today, to engage in the global debate about \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  and to blow away the hot air that swirls around the subject, any business needs to start by being a responsible employer," says Julia Cleverdon, chief executive of Business in the Community.\par \par \uc2 "What doesn't work and doesn't achieve a positive impact on society is to attempt to bolt social responsibility on to existing structures by throwing time, money and effort at neighbourhood renewal or the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  while your own people at work are lacking in motivation and skills and your supply chains feel badly treated."\par \par \uc2 National Grid Transco, another short-listed company, found an imaginative way to encourage its 14,000 UK employees to take action to improve workplace health and safety. The international energy delivery business launched a "safety charity challenge" in which the company donated money to Mencap and Enable, the disability charities, each time an employee identified a hazard at work that was subsequently removed.\par \par \uc2 The scope was broadened in 2001 to include reducing traffic accidents involving Transco vehicles. Employees were also able to choose local charities to benefit from half of the donation, with the other half going to Mencap and Enable. Work-related injuries fell to 117 in 2003-4, the company's lowest-ever annual figure, from 543 in 1998.\par \par \uc2 The Healthy Workplaces award links into BITC's newest campaign, Business Action on Health, by recognising different ways in which companies can improve the wellbeing of their employees. New research conducted for the campaign jointly by BITC and vielife, a consultancy on workplace health and productivity, finds that business leaders are interested in employee health and wellbeing but are uncertain about how to measure them or indeed about what matters to the business.\par \par \uc2 Mental health, for example, is seen as a low priority, in spite of the complicated problem of stress, which is now one of the two most commonly reported causes of work-related sickness absence, along with musculoskeletal disorders.\par \par \uc2 The research, consisting of an online survey completed by 454 chief executives, finance directors and HR directors, shows that companies still tend to focus on measuring sickness rather than promoting health. Only 43 per cent of HR directors measure health through risk assessments or health check-ups.\par \par \uc2 Last November, the government published a white paper, Choosing Health, including a chapter entitled Work and Health that was aimed at employers. Yet 92 per cent of the chief executives and finance directors, and 81 per cent of the HR directors, had read nothing about this. About 70 per cent of respondents agreed that their organisation would benefit from a standard way of benchmarking and measuring health and wellbeing.\par \par \uc2 The lack of clarity about what constitutes best practice is reflected in big variations in the quality and type of programmes submitted in the 30 entries to the award, BITC says. To achieve a big tick from the awards' independent assessors, entries need to demonstrate both qualitative measures, such as testimonials, and quantitative evidence. Some entries to the new awards were short on statistics measuring progress and outcomes, something that the charity hopes will improve next year.\par \par \uc2 Ms Cleverdon says that the theme of being a responsible employer links the healthy workplaces award with this year's other two new awards: the HBOS Supply Chain award and the Oracle International Award.\par \par \uc2 "Responsibility and care for people is being pushed down the supply chains, partly under pressure from existing employees and partly under pressure from customers," she says. "Investing in the supply chain is a direct investment both in the value of the business and in the target economy."\par \par \uc2 Big ticks go to Boots, BT and Ricoh UK for the supply chain award. Boots, for example, has a verification programme that is designed to ensure suppliers comply with legislation and the company's code of conduct for ethical trading. In-house assessment teams visit European and Asian suppliers to check wages and benefits, health and safety, and issues such as whether there are underage workers. Employees are encouraged to give their views, either anonymously or in discussion groups.\par \par \uc2 Since the start of the programme by the health and beauty retailer in 2002, the verification teams have identified more than 2,500 breaches, for which they have required remedial action. Benefits include efficiency gains among suppliers, lower staff turnover and better relations between Boots and socially responsible investment funds.\par \par \uc2 The international award focuses on Africa and is made in association with the International Business Leaders Forum and the UK government-sponsored Commission for Africa. Big ticks in this new category go to Anglo American, Citigroup, GlaxoSmithKline, Merchants and SABMiller.\par \par \uc2 SABMiller, the international brewing group, introduced Eagle Lager, an affordable beer made from locally-produced sorghum in Uganda, as an alternative to the crude, home-made alcohol consumed by many communities that could not afford to buy beer.\par \par \uc2 Four years later, the new lager has a market share of about 20 per cent and has become the top brand of Nile Breweries, the group's Ugandan operation. About 3,500 Ugandan farmers have contracts to grow the sorghum and the company's relations with the government have greatly improved.\par \par \uc2 The company says the project demonstrates both the benefits of approaching development from a commercial perspective and the central role that the private sector can play in assisting African countries to achieve the United Nations' Millennium Development Goals.\par \par \uc2 *Centrica Diversity Award\par \par \uc2 Ford of Britain (DEAR - Diversity Equality Assessment Review)\par \par \uc2 PricewaterhouseCoopers (Diversity, how we leverage success)\par \par \uc2 Royal Mail Group (Diversity Inclusion Programme)\par \par \uc2 The Britannia Group (Business as usual)\par \par \uc2 Re-accredited\par \par \uc2 BSkyB (BSkyB Disability Strategy)\par \par \uc2 Everton Football Club (Disability Football Development Programme)\par \par \uc2 Inland Revenue (Diversity - Good For Business, Good For People)\par \par \uc2 *Rentokil Initial Skills\par \par \uc2 for Life Award\par \par \uc2 Serco Group (Skills for You)\par \par \uc2 VT Shipbuilding\par \par \uc2 Re-accredited\par \par \uc2 Walkers Snack Foods\par \par \uc2 *UnumProvident Healthy Workplaces Award\par \par \uc2 3M United Kingdom (Aycliffe plant) (3M Aycliffe Working for Health)\par \par \uc2 AstraZeneca (Health and Wellbeing in AstraZeneca)\par \par \uc2 Ernst &Young (The Best Place to be - Healthy Working at Ernst &Young)\par \par \uc2 London Underground (Stress Plan)\par \par \uc2 National Grid Transco (Safety Charity Challenge)\par \par \uc2 Northbrook Technology of Northern Ireland (Healthy Working \b \highlight22\uc2 Environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 )\par \par \uc2 Standard Life Healthcare (Health and Wellbeing Programme)\par \par \uc2 *Dollond Aitchison Cause Related Marketing Award\par \par \uc2 Blockbuster Entertainment (Blockbuster supports Starlight Children's Foundation)\par \par \uc2 Debenhams (Debenhams and the Breast Cancer Campaign)\par \par \uc2 ScottishPower (Tackling Global Climate Change Through Green Energy Products)\par \par \uc2 The Bingo Association (Bingo for Breakthrough)\par \par \uc2 The Somerfield Group (Reaching Out - A Partnership between The Somerfield Group and the Muscular Dystrophy Campaign)\par \par \uc2 Vodafone UK (The Vodafone National Autistic Society Partnership 'Better relationships through communication')\par \par