h Roth ("Rules on corporate ethics could help, not hinder, multinationals", June 21) laments a lack of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  in developing countries. Furthermore, he calls on the countries of the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development to come up with binding CSR standards and export them to the developing world through global legal enforcement of the OECD Guidelines for Multinational Enterprises, which have so far been a non-binding set of recommendations for good business conduct. Mr Roth could not be more wrong.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 First of all, contrary to what he suggests, businesses from OECD countries are not the problem regarding human rights, labour standards and \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  protection in developing countries. In fact, the opposite is true. Foreign companies' investment has a very positive impact on host countries' economies due to the financial, technological and managerial resources it brings with it.\par \par \uc2 Many companies decide voluntarily to invest significant amounts in activities that benefit the communities where they operate. They do this because they believe their shareholders, customers and employees will give them credit for this, and not because the OECD has forced them into it.\par \par \uc2 Second, developing countries do not need new rules on corporate behaviour imposed on them by industrialised countries. They have most of the necessary rules in place but often do not enforce them. Thus, developing countries must improve their public governance. This means ensuring accountability and transparency, fighting bribe solicitation and corruption and rigorously enforcing the rule of law. Good governance is the key to sustainable business development, which in turn facilitates companies' CSR efforts.\par \par \uc2 Companies and multilateral institutions can help. The healthier the overall business \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the better companies can add voluntary CSR initiatives to their core business operations. As for multilateral institutions such as OECD and the World Bank, their role is to assist developing countries with sound policy recommendations, highlighting best practices and providing technical and/ or financial assistance that enables developing countries to build capacities for good governance.\par \par \uc2 Helping developing countries to improve public governance and to create favourable business environments will do much more for promoting the goals of CSR than exporting industrialised countries' rules to their doorstep.\par \par \uc2 Thomas R. Vant, Secretary General, Business and Industry Advisory Committee to the OECD, 75016 Paris, France \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 20050629E112.035\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\cl