n: $17,000\par \par \uc2 Companies hiring the most 2004 full-time graduates\par \par \uc2 Nestle, Royal Dutch Shell: 4 each\par \par \uc2 Philips: 3\par \par \uc2 Three of the most famous graduates of the M.B.A. program\par \par \uc2 Nick Shreiber (class of 1975), CEO, Tetra Pak\par \par \uc2 K.Y. Lee (class of 1990), chairman, BenQ Corp.\par \par \uc2 Jurgen Fischer (class of 1988), president, commercial operations group, Hilton International\par \par \uc2 THE RECRUITERS SPEAK\par \par \uc2 IMD's most impressive features\par \par \uc2 "Global mind-set"\par \par \uc2 "Very mature group, extensive work experience"\par \par \uc2 "Excellent general-management skills"\par \par \uc2 IMD's major shortcomings\par \par \uc2 "High expectations of salary and pace of promotions"\par \par \uc2 "Too few female faculty members and M.B.A.s"\par \par \uc2 "Acts too much like a business"\par \par \uc2 2. ESADE\par \par \uc2 Escuela Superior de Administracion y Direccion de Empresas, established in 1958 in Barcelona, Spain, by a group of businesspeople in collaboration with the Society of Jesus, began life with only undergraduate and doctorate programs but added the M.B.A. degree in 1964. Today, it has campuses in both Barcelona and Madrid and offers four varieties of M.B.A. degrees: one-year, 18-month, part-time and executive.\par \par \uc2 ESADE's general-management M.B.A. program is bilingual; by the time students graduate, they are expected to be fluent in English and Spanish. ESADE students also can participate in exchange programs at some 60 business schools around the world.\par \par \uc2 After a month focused on basic business principles, students in the 18-month program follow three stages of study: general management and the business \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the integration of strategy with business functions, and global management. In the second year, they can major in such areas as public-sector management, finance, marketing, business policy, human resources and information systems. Students also create a business plan to hone their entrepreneurial skills.\par \par \uc2 Given its religious roots, ESADE emphasizes personal values and corporate social and environmental responsibility through both the M.B.A. curriculum and research at its Institute for the Individual, Corporations and Society.\par \par \uc2 One of ESADE's newest offerings is an international master's degree in tourism and leisure. The degree was created as part of an agreement with the Spanish government and tourism companies to improve training of industry managers.\par \par \uc2 In The Wall Street Journal/Harris Interactive survey, recruiters gave ESADE graduates their highest marks for communication and interpersonal skills and the ability to work well in teams. ESADE received its lowest ratings for faculty expertise and the likelihood of hiring stars.\par \par \uc2 Graduates "are well-rounded in their technical knowledge, managerial skills, international perspective and values," says Jose Lopez, a survey respondent who recruits at ESADE as an executive-search consultant for Russell Reynolds Associates. He sees the school's primary academic strengths in marketing and human resources and believes it is "leading in Spain on the topic of emotional intelligence and leadership."\par \par \uc2 ESADE on ESADE\par \par \uc2 (Data provided by the ESADE Business School)\par \par \uc2 M.B.A. enrollment: 604\par \par \uc2 Full-time: 195\par \par \uc2 Part-time: 239\par \par \uc2 Executive program: 170\par \par \uc2 Annual tuition: $29,295\par \par \uc2 Annual room and board: $15,296\par \par \uc2 Profile of Full-Time Students\par \par \uc2 GMAT score: 630 (mean); N.A. (median)\par \par \uc2 Years of full-time work experience: 4.5 (mean); N.A. (median)\par \par \uc2 Demographics\par \par \uc2 Male: 80%\par \par \uc2 Female: 20%\par \par \uc2 Spanish citizens/residents: 28%\par \par \uc2 Foreign nationals: 72%\par \par \uc2 Class of 2004 Employment Data\par \par \uc2 Percentage of job-seeking full-time graduates who:\par \par \uc2 Received offers prior to or within 3 months of graduation: 89%\par \par \uc2 Accepted offers prior to or within 3 months of graduation: 89%\par \par \uc2 Average compensation of full-time graduates who accepted employment\par \par \uc2 Annual base salary: $72,093\par \par \uc2 Signing bonus: $11,790\par \par \uc2 Other guaranteed compensation: $18,822\par \par \uc2 Companies hiring the most 2004 full-time graduates\par \par \uc2 L'Oreal: 3\par \par \uc2 Lear: 3\par \par \uc2 McKinsey: 2\par \par \uc2 Three of the most famous graduates of the M.B.A. program\par \par \uc2 Enrique Rueda-Sabater (class of 1979), director of corporate strategy group, World Bank\par \par \uc2 Ignacio Fonts (class of 1982), vice president, inkjet supplies, HP Americas\par \par \uc2 Ferran Soriano (class of 1990), vice president, operations and finance, FC Barcelona\par \par \uc2 THE RECRUITERS SPEAK\par \par \uc2 ESADE's most impressive features\par \par \uc2 "Strategic and holistic view of business dynamics"\par \par \uc2 "Capacity for adapting to any circumstance"\par \par \uc2 "Social/humanistic profile"\par \par \uc2 ESADE's major shortcomings\par \par \uc2 "Lack of international experience"\par \par \uc2 "Less visionary"\par \par \uc2 "Lack of self-confidence"\par \par \uc2 3. CARNEGIE MELLON (TEPPER)\par \par \uc2 The profile of Carnegie Mellon appears among the leaders in the National ranking, where the school also placed third.\par \par \uc2 4. IPADE\par \par \uc2 IPADE's profile appears among the leaders in the Regional ranking, where the school placed fifth.\par \par \uc2 5. UNIVERSITY OF LONDON (London Business School)\par \par \uc2 Founded in 1965, London Business School offers one of the leading M.B.A. programs in Europe and attracts a very international faculty and student body, with 86% of its full-time graduates from outside the U.K. and its professors representing 23 countries.\par \par \uc2 Students can choose academic concentrations in finance, marketing, entrepreneurial management, technology management, strategy or international business. More than two-thirds of the graduates typically take jobs in financial services and management consulting.\par \par \uc2 London Business School encourages student interaction with the business world. The full-time program culminates with the second-year project in which small student teams consult for such clients as IBM and Nike. As part of its leadership focus, the school assigns students to a "shadowing project" that requires them to observe a manager on the job for up to five days and then submit a report on their observations. Many managers say they believe they learn as much or more than the students from the exercise.\par \par \uc2 Most students seek a corporate internship during the summer between the two years of the M.B.A. program. But London Business School offers M.B.A.s another option: the Summer Entrepreneurship Experience, which provides entrepreneurial companies with "a highly motivated and qualified extra pair of hands at a low cost."\par \par \uc2 In addition to the full-time M.B.A., London Business School offers two executive M.B.A. programs, one of which is a partnership with Columbia Business School in New York. During the 20-month trans-Atlantic program, students alternate their studies between the two schools.\par \par \uc2 In The Wall Street Journal/Harris Interactive survey, recruiters gave the school its highest ratings for students' analytical and problem-solving abilities, international knowledge and experience, and communication and interpersonal skills. The school received its lowest scores for the career-services office, value for the money invested in the recruiting effort, and students' awareness of corporate-citizenship issues.\par \par \uc2 "The quality of students is very strong, particularly with respect to their ability to act independently and get things done and their overall 