r, Tobias Buck and Stephanie Kirchgaessner ("Brussels braces for a US lobbying invasion", October 3) give the impression that European lobbyists are inactive, with purely a mandate to monitor new legislation. By contrast, the article suggests, our US lobbyist colleagues will work with their clients in order to achieve legislative results. Anyone who has witnessed Reach will know that European lobbyists are not quite so timid, and in that respect we probably share a lot of common values, even if our more modest approach distinguishes us.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Europe has realised that lobbying casts many images; most often it is associated with ugly politics. For example, in Europe political donations are frowned on whereas in the US it is commonplace. Of growing interest in Europe is that corporate lobbying should be fully integrated with \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 . In a report "Influencing power: reviewing the conduct and content of corporate lobbying" earlier this year by SustainAbility and WWF, the authors argued that lobbyists should take leadership for promoting better legislation. In this respect, European industry is learning that stricter and stronger protection of the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and social policy should be central to our policy ambitions. For these reasons, I am not sure the same brash US lobbying techniques described by the authors are welcome in Europe.\par \par \uc2 Nick Farnsworth,\par \par \uc2 ADS Insig